{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778615246284,"sessionID":"ses_1e24c82bdffe2D3pcsN52IMQOq","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_g9UKVbmgAo28IiTcIUXWUCL1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r12s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r12s0\n+title: \"Pipeline low-half MUL partials\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The best current bench result came from moving low-half MUL out of the\n+  common ALU cone, but the standalone mul_unit still contains a full 32x32\n+  product path that must meet the FPGA clock. Prior attempts show that\n+  reintroducing multiplier logic into EX, folding MUL into the shared M unit,\n+  or adding operand-class bypasses regresses QoR. A narrower MUL-only internal\n+  datapath keeps the successful isolation while attacking the remaining\n+  multiplier timing path.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Rewrite rtl/mul_unit.sv so the real hardware path computes RV32 MUL[31:0]\n+  over a few registered partial-product phases, for example by capturing\n+  16x16 low and cross partials, then summing only the low 32 result bits in a\n+  later cycle. Keep the same start/result_valid/result_ready interface, keep\n+  the RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS branch simple and equivalent, and let EX continue to\n+  hold only while mul_unit is busy. This adds one or two cycles only to sparse\n+  low-half MUL instructions, while potentially replacing the current 32x32\n+  register-to-register product path with shorter 16x16 multiply and 32-bit add\n+  stages for better Tang Nano Fmax.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/mul_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Replace the single-cycle 32x32 real-product datapath with a small multicycle low-half partial-product pipeline while preserving the existing handshake and ALTOPS behavior.\"\n+  - file: test/test_mul_unit.py\n+    description: \"Update mul_unit tests to wait for result_valid, check busy during the new compute phases, and retain exact low-half and ALTOPS result vectors.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r12s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r12s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r12s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r12s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,29 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r12s0\n+title: \"Pipeline low-half MUL partials\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The best current bench result came from moving low-half MUL out of the\n+  common ALU cone, but the standalone mul_unit still contains a full 32x32\n+  product path that must meet the FPGA clock. Prior attempts show that\n+  reintroducing multiplier logic into EX, folding MUL into the shared M unit,\n+  or adding operand-class bypasses regresses QoR. A narrower MUL-only internal\n+  datapath keeps the successful isolation while attacking the remaining\n+  multiplier timing path.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Rewrite rtl/mul_unit.sv so the real hardware path computes RV32 MUL[31:0]\n+  over a few registered partial-product phases, for example by capturing\n+  16x16 low and cross partials, then summing only the low 32 result bits in a\n+  later cycle. Keep the same start/result_valid/result_ready interface, keep\n+  the RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS branch simple and equivalent, and let EX continue to\n+  hold only while mul_unit is busy. This adds one or two cycles only to sparse\n+  low-half MUL instructions, while potentially replacing the current 32x32\n+  register-to-register product path