{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778618644281,"sessionID":"ses_1e212da49ffej86GRvXv1270PJ","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_S5qNOb5dNQPxN3T8gghPP7po","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r15s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r15s0\n+title: \"Retimed divider iteration\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The best bench-core gains have come from removing or retiming RV32M logic\n+  that affects FPGA Fmax while CoreMark rarely pays the added slow-operation\n+  latency. The remaining real DIV/REM loop in rtl/m_unit.sv still combines a\n+  33-bit shifted-remainder compare, conditional subtract, quotient update, and\n+  remainder feedback in one cycle. That path is independent of the already\n+  isolated low-half MUL fast path and is a plausible residual timing limiter.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Split the real-hardware divider loop into two shorter registered phases per\n+  quotient bit: one phase forms the shifted remainder and comparison decision,\n+  and the next phase applies the conditional subtract and updates quotient,\n+  dividend, and remainder state. Keep divide-by-zero and signed-overflow\n+  shortcuts unchanged, keep the ALTOPS formal branch unchanged, and preserve\n+  the existing result_valid/result_ready contract. DIV/REM latency increases,\n+  but CoreMark should execute those operations rarely enough that any cycle\n+  cost is outweighed by a modest Tang Nano Fmax improvement.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/m_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Retiming the real DIV/REM iteration into compare and subtract/update phases while preserving shortcuts, ALTOPS behavior, and the existing handshake.\"\n+  - file: test/test_alu.py\n+    description: \"Retain or extend DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU vectors for divide-by-zero, signed overflow, negative operands, and exact remainder signs after the divider retime.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r15s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r15s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r15s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r15s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,27 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r15s0\n+title: \"Retimed divider iteration\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The best bench-core gains have come from removing or retiming RV32M logic\n+  that affects FPGA Fmax while CoreMark rarely pays the added slow-operation\n+  latency. The remaining real DIV/REM loop in rtl/m_unit.sv still combines a\n+  33-bit shifted-remainder compare, conditional subtract, quotient update, and\n+  remainder feedback in one cycle. That path is independent of the already\n+  isolated low-half MUL fast path and is a plausible residual timing limiter.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Split the real-hardware divider loop into two shorter registered phases per\n+  quotient bit: one phase forms the shifted remainder and comparison decision,\n+  and the next phase applies the conditional subtract and updates quotient,\n+  dividend, and remainder state. Keep divide-by-zero and signed-overflow\n+  shortcuts unchanged, keep the ALTOPS formal branch unchanged, and preserve\n+  the existing result_valid/result_ready contract. DIV/REM latency increases,\n+  but CoreMark should execute those operations rarely enough that any cycle\n+  cost is outweighed by a modest Tang Nano Fmax improvement.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: 