{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778596718848,"sessionID":"ses_1e362936fffedm6C3qmHOFrY5W","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_SYa27enp68fI8cSDNum22zcm","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r2s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r2s0\n+title: \"Trim low-half MUL partial products\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best design already removed rare high-half multiply and divide\n+  operations from the common EX result cone, but RV32M low-half MUL remains a\n+  single-cycle 32x32 multiply in the fast ALU. CoreMark benefits from keeping\n+  MUL single-cycle, yet RV32 MUL only needs product bits [31:0], so the high x\n+  high partial product and some upper carry logic are unnecessary FPGA work.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the generic low-half `a * b` implementation in rtl/alu.sv with an\n+  explicit low-32 partial-product decomposition using 16-bit limbs: low x low\n+  plus the lower half of the two cross products shifted by 16. This should let\n+  synthesis drop the unused high x high multiplier work and map the remaining\n+  pieces more cleanly to Tang Nano DSP/LUT resources while preserving the\n+  one-cycle ALU_MUL latency that CoreMark needs. Keep the RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS\n+  substitute unchanged and add focused MUL low-half carry vectors so RV32M\n+  bit-exactness remains covered.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n+    description: \"Compute ALU_MUL's low 32 bits from 16-bit partial products instead of a full generic 32x32 product, leaving ALTOPS behavior unchanged.\"\n+  - file: test/test_alu.py\n+    description: \"Add MUL low-half edge vectors that exercise cross-product carries and discarded high-half bits.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r2s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r2s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r2s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r2s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,26 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r2s0\n+title: \"Trim low-half MUL partial products\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best design already removed rare high-half multiply and divide\n+  operations from the common EX result cone, but RV32M low-half MUL remains a\n+  single-cycle 32x32 multiply in the fast ALU. CoreMark benefits from keeping\n+  MUL single-cycle, yet RV32 MUL only needs product bits [31:0], so the high x\n+  high partial product and some upper carry logic are unnecessary FPGA work.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the generic low-half `a * b` implementation in rtl/alu.sv with an\n+  explicit low-32 partial-product decomposition using 16-bit limbs: low x low\n+  plus the lower half of the two cross products shifted by 16. This should let\n+  synthesis drop the unused high x high multiplier work and map the remaining\n+  pieces more cleanly to Tang Nano DSP/LUT resources while preserving the\n+  one-cycle ALU_MUL latency that CoreMark needs. Keep the RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS\n+  substitute unchanged and add focused MUL low-half carry vectors so RV32M\n+  bit-exactness remains covered.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n+    description: \"Compute ALU_MUL's low 32 bits from 16-bit partial products instead of a full generic 32x32 product, leaving ALTOPS behavior unchanged.\"\n+  - file: test/test_alu.py\n+    description: \"Add MUL low-half edge vectors that exercise cross-product carries and discarded high-half bits.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r2s0.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r2s0.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r2s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r2s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r2s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,26 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r2s0\n+title: \"Trim low-half MUL partial products\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best design already removed rare high-half multiply and divide\n+  operations from the common EX result cone, but RV32M low-half MUL remains a\n+  single-cycle 32x32 multiply in the fast ALU. CoreMark benefits from keeping\n+  MUL single-cycle, yet RV32 MUL only needs product bits [31:0], so the high x\n+  high partial product and some upper carry logic are unnecessary FPGA work.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the generic low-half `a * b` implementation in rtl/alu.sv with an\n+  explicit low-32 partial-product decomposition using 16-bit limbs: low x low\n+  plus the lower half of the two cross products shifted by 16. This should let\n+  synthesis drop the unused high x high multiplier work and map the remaining\n+  pieces more cleanly to Tang Nano DSP/LUT resources while preserving the\n+  one-cycle ALU_MUL latency that CoreMark needs. Keep the RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS\n+  substitute unchanged and add focused MUL low-half carry vectors so RV32M\n+  bit-exactness remains covered.\n+expected_impact:\n+  