{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778600059185,"sessionID":"ses_1e32f17f0ffeU8A3qXHweaPlBJ","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_iv3duZvl2xqNZdlsChgcW8ju","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r4s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r4s0\n+title: \"Case-based MEM byte lanes\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best core has already moved rare high-half multiply and divide\n+  work out of the common EX path, so the next safest micro-optimization is a\n+  hot load/store datapath cleanup rather than another predictor or bypass.\n+  CoreMark performs many byte, halfword, and word memory accesses, and the MEM\n+  stage currently builds masks with variable shifts and extracts load data with\n+  a variable word shift before sign extension. Even if synthesis simplifies\n+  some of this, the generic shifter/mask form can add LUT depth and routing on\n+  a path that every load reaches.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Rewrite the MEM-stage byte-lane logic as explicit case statements keyed by\n+  address bits and access width. Generate store masks, replicated write data,\n+  load byte/halfword selection, and RVFI masks directly per lane instead of\n+  using `<<` and `>> (addr[1:0] * 8)` expressions. This preserves the existing\n+  one-cycle MEM latency, dmem handshake behavior, misalignment trapping, and\n+  nret=1 RVFI contract while giving yosys/nextpnr a smaller mux network for the\n+  load-data and mask paths. The expected gain is mostly Fmax with no intentional\n+  CoreMark cycle-count change.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Replace generic variable shift/mask byte-lane generation with explicit lane case logic for loads, stores, and RVFI masks while preserving misalignment gating.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r4s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r4s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r4s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r4s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,27 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r4s0\n+title: \"Case-based MEM byte lanes\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best core has already moved rare high-half multiply and divide\n+  work out of the common EX path, so the next safest micro-optimization is a\n+  hot load/store datapath cleanup rather than another predictor or bypass.\n+  CoreMark performs many byte, halfword, and word memory accesses, and the MEM\n+  stage currently builds masks with variable shifts and extracts load data with\n+  a variable word shift before sign extension. Even if synthesis simplifies\n+  some of this, the generic shifter/mask form can add LUT depth and routing on\n+  a path that every load reaches.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Rewrite the MEM-stage byte-lane logic as explicit case statements keyed by\n+  address bits and access width. Generate store masks, replicated write data,\n+  load byte/halfword selection, and RVFI masks directly per lane instead of\n+  using `<<` and `>> (addr[1:0] * 8)` expressions. This preserves the existing\n+  one-cycle MEM latency, dmem handshake behavior, misalignment trapping, and\n+  nret=1 RVFI contract while giving yosys/nextpnr a smaller mux network for the\n+  load-data and mask paths. The expected gain is mostly Fmax with no intentional\n+  CoreMark cycle-count change.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - fil