{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778601695415,"sessionID":"ses_1e31752b1ffeBJruno34LH2hjx","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_K2jZdXou6T4ZMg1SbZcDFIIl","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r5s1.yaml","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r5s1.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260512-002-r5s1\n2: title: \"Register WB forwarding data\"\n3: category: structural\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The r4 structural win registered forwarding selects, which suggests the EX\n6:   operand cone is still timing-sensitive after the slow RV32M work was moved\n7:   off the common path. MEM/WB forwarding still feeds EX through the live WB\n8:   write-data mux, so a dependent instruction forwarded from WB carries\n9:   mem_to_reg selection into the EX operand mux, ALU, and one-cycle MUL path.\n10:   That mux is small, but it sits on the hottest every-cycle datapath and does\n11:   not buy CoreMark any IPC.\n12: hypothesis: |\n13:   Add a registered final writeback value at the MEM/WB boundary and use it for\n14:   the regfile write port, RVFI rd_wdata, and MEM/WB-to-EX forwarding. MEM still\n15:   computes load extension and ALU-vs-load selection before the MEM/WB flop; EX\n16:   then sees only a registered 32-bit forwarding value rather than the live\n17:   WB-stage result mux. This preserves the five-stage retirement point, load-use\n18:   bubble policy, dmem hold semantics, and nret=1 RVFI contract while shortening\n19:   the post-r4 EX operand path with no intentional cycle-count change.\n20: expected_impact:\n21:   fitness_delta_pct: 2\n22:   confidence: medium\n23: changes:\n24:   - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n25:     description: \"Add a final writeback-data field to mem_wb_t so the MEM/WB boundary carries the value used for writes and forwarding.\"\n26:   - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n27:     description: \"Compute and register the final WB data alongside existing read_data and alu_result fields, retaining it across hold_wb stalls.\"\n28:   - file: rtl/wb_stage.sv\n29:     description: \"Drive w_data from the registered MEM/WB value instead of recomputing the mem_to_reg mux in the WB-stage combinational path.\"\n\n(End of file - total 29 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260512-002-r5s1\ntitle: \"Register WB forwarding data\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The r4 structural win registered forwarding selects, which suggests the EX\n  operand cone is still timing-sensitive after the slow RV32M work was moved\n  off the common path. MEM/WB forwarding still feeds EX through the live WB\n  write-data mux, so a dependent instruction forwarded from WB carries\n  mem_to_reg selection into the EX operand mux, ALU, and one-cycle MUL path.\n  That mux is small, but it sits on the hottest every-cycle datapath and does\n  not buy CoreMark any IPC.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a registered final writeback value at the MEM/WB boundary and use it for\n  the regfile write port, RVFI rd_wdata, and MEM/WB-to-EX forwarding. MEM still\n  computes load extension and ALU-vs-load selection before the MEM/WB flop; EX\n  then sees only a registered 32-bit forwarding value rather than the live\n  WB-stage result mux. This preserves the five-stage retirement point, load-use\n  bubble policy, dmem hold semantics, and nret=1 RVFI contract while shortening\n  the post-r4 EX operand path with no intentional cycle-count change.\nexpected_impact:","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r5s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778601695410,"end":1778601695414}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0d5d94f2e5a9e3b6016a034edf4b1081938bcde11843a38627"}},"id":"prt_e1cec189e001DTAG0t0H6uL2l0","sessionID":"ses_1e31752b1ffeBJruno34LH2hjx","messageID":"msg_e1cebd9d2001hJBYVxOCmtkDw3"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778601695416,"sessionID":"ses_1e31752b1ffeBJruno34LH2hjx","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_jflIWFjAVNzjkAbc98hdRHg8","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r5s2.yaml","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r5s2.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260512-003-r5s2\n2: title: \"Decode-stage JAL target predictor\"\n3: category: predictor\n4: motivation: |\n5:   Prior predictor attempts lost fitness because they put branch immediate decode,\n6:   tag compares, target arrays, or RAS logic directly in the fetch next-PC path.\n7:   CoreMark still contains direct calls and unconditional jumps, and those are\n8:   deterministic once the instruction is visible in decode. A narrower predictor\n9:   can recover some redirect bubbles without adding conditional branch direction\n10:   state or a BTB-style lookup to every fetch.\n11: hypothesis: |\n12:   Add an early direct-JAL target predictor in decode: when ID sees an aligned\n13:   JAL instruction, compute pc+J_imm using the existing decoded immediate path\n14:   and redirect IF one stage earlier than the normal EX redirect. Carry a compact\n15:   predicted-direct-jump bit and predicted target through ID/EX so EX suppresses\n16:   the ordinary JAL redirect when the prediction matches, and recovers normally\n17:   for misaligned targets or any mismatch. This focuses the predictor on\n18:   unconditional direct control flow, avoiding the failed conditional-branch,\n19:   loop-BTB, and RAS structures while still saving bubbles on CoreMark calls and\n20:   direct jumps.\n21: expected_impact:\n22:   fitness_delta_pct: 2\n23:   confidence: low\n24: changes:\n25:   - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n26:     description: \"Add compact direct-JAL prediction metadata to IF/ID or ID/EX pipeline bundles for EX redirect suppression and recovery.\"\n27:   - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n28:     description: \"Detect aligned JAL instructions in decode, compute the early target from the existing immediate path, and emit prediction metadata with the instruction.\"\n29:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n30:     description: \"Wire the decode-stage predicted redirect into the IF stage with EX redirect taking priority, preserving nret=1 RVFI retirement semantics.\"\n31:   - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n32:     description: \"Accept an early predicted redirect target while keeping reset, stalls, and resolved EX redirects prioritized for correctness.\"\n33:   - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n34:     description: \"Suppress the normal JAL redirect when decode prediction matches the resolved target; otherwise use the existing redirect recovery and misalignment trap behavior.\"\n\n(End of file - total 34 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260512-003-r5s2\ntitle: \"Decode-stage JAL target predictor\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  Prior predictor attempts lost fitness because they put branch immediate decode,\n  tag compares, target arrays, or RAS logic directly in the fetch next-PC path.\n  CoreMark still contains direct calls and unconditional jumps, and those are\n  deterministic once the instruction is visible in decode. A narrower predictor\n  can recover some redirect bubbles without adding conditional branch direction\n  state or a BTB-style lookup to every fetch.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add an early direct-JAL target predictor in decode: when ID sees an aligned\n  JAL instruction, compute pc+J_imm using the existing decoded immediate path\n  and redirect IF one stage earlier than the normal EX redirect. Carry a compact\n  predicted-direct-jump bit and predicted target through ID/EX so EX suppresses\n  the ordinary JAL redirect when the prediction matches, and recovers normally\n  for misaligned targets or any mismatch. This focuses the predictor on\n  unconditional direct control flow, avoiding the failed conditional-branch,\n  loop-BTB, and RAS structures while still saving bubbles on CoreMark calls and\n  direct jumps.","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r5s2.yaml","time":{"start":1778601695412,"end":1778601695415}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0d5d94f2e5a9e3b6016a034edf4b248193b2bf6952d303216a"}},"id":"prt_e1cec18b3002c7AARomgdKk44g","sessionID":"ses_1e31752b1ffeBJruno34LH2hjx","messageID":"msg_e1cebd9d2001hJBYVxOCmtkDw3"}}
