{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778601726055,"sessionID":"ses_1e31752b1ffeBJruno34LH2hjx","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_FbQWT2nv62j0nnuZtWzvIOjQ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r5s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r5s0\n+title: \"Source-aware load-use stalls\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current hazard unit treats both raw rs1 and rs2 bitfields as live source\n+  operands for every instruction. That is conservative, but it can insert a\n+  one-cycle load-use bubble when the following instruction is LUI, AUIPC, JAL,\n+  EBREAK/FENCE, or an I-type instruction whose immediate bits merely alias the\n+  previous load destination. CoreMark contains many load/immediate/control-flow\n+  sequences, so avoiding these false bubbles should improve cycles without\n+  adding a bypass path or fetch-side predictor logic.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add small source-usage qualification for load-use detection and decode-time\n+  forwarding select generation. The hazard unit should only compare a pending\n+  load destination against rs1 when the IF/ID instruction architecturally reads\n+  rs1, and only against rs2 when it architecturally reads rs2. Keep true\n+  load-use bubbles for OP, BRANCH, STORE, LOAD/OP-IMM/JALR rs1 dependencies,\n+  preserve the existing no-MEM-bypass policy, and leave RVFI retirement and\n+  trap behavior unchanged. This is a localized IPC micro-optimization with far\n+  less timing risk than the failed MEM-to-EX load bypass.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Qualify load-use hazard comparisons with compact IF/ID source-use decoding so unused raw rs fields do not create false bubbles.\"\n+  - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Optionally gate decode-time forwarding select comparisons by the same source-use bits, preserving forwarding for all architecturally read operands.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the IF/ID instruction or derived source-use flags into the hazard and forwarding units without changing the nret=1 top-level IO contract.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r5s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r5s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r5s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r5s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,30 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r5s0\n+title: \"Source-aware load-use stalls\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current hazard unit treats both raw rs1 and rs2 bitfields as live source\n+  operands for every instruction. That is conservative, but it can insert a\n+  one-cycle load-use bubble when the following instruction is LUI, AUIPC, JAL,\n+  EBREAK/FENCE, or an I-type instruction whose immediate bits merely alias the\n+  previous load destination. CoreMark contains many load/immediate/control-flow\n+  sequences, so avoiding these false bubbles should improve cycles without\n+  adding a bypass path or fetch-side predictor logic.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add small source-usage qualification for load-use detection and decode-time\n+  forwarding select generation. The hazard unit should only compare a pending\n+  load destination against rs1 when the IF/ID instruction architecturally reads\n+  rs1, and only against rs2 when it architecturally reads rs2. Keep true\n+  load-use bubbles for OP, BRANCH, STORE, LOAD/OP-IMM/JALR rs1 dependencies,\n+  preserve the existing no-MEM-bypass policy, and leave RVFI retirement and\n+  trap behavior unchanged. This is a localized IPC micro-optimization with far\n+  less timing risk than the failed MEM-to-EX load bypass.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Qualify load-use hazard comparisons with compact IF/ID source-use decoding so unused raw rs fields do not create false bubbles.\"\n+  - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Optionally gate decode-time forwarding select comparisons by the same source-use bits, preserving forwarding for all architecturally read operands.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the IF/ID instruction or derived source-use flags into the hazard and forwarding units without changing the nret=1 top-level IO contract.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r5s0.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r5s0.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r5s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r5s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r5s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,30 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r5s0\n+title: \"Source-aware load-use stalls\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current hazard unit treats both raw rs1 and rs2 bitfields as live source\n+  operands for every instruction. That is conservative, but it can insert a\n+  one-cycle load-use bubble when the following instruction i