{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778608810168,"sessionID":"ses_1e2ab05a7ffe27yOOlTJSyuNN8","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_n8cdOb1CAlegoHbF0wI3iumL","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r9s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r9s0\n+title: \"Isolate fast EX result mux\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best result came from registering low-half MUL so the 32x32\n+  multiplier no longer sits in the common ALU cone. However, normal ADD,\n+  load-address, branch-adjacent, and jump-link results still feed the EX/MEM\n+  register through a shared result select that includes low-half MUL and the\n+  slow M-unit result. CoreMark executes M operations sparsely, so keeping\n+  those M-result inputs on the every-cycle fast EX register input may cost\n+  Fmax without improving IPC.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Rewrite the EX-stage commit result selection so ordinary single-cycle\n+  instructions drive EX/MEM from a fast result path containing only the ALU\n+  result or JAL/JALR link value, while low-half MUL and slow M results are\n+  selected only in the result-valid commit branch. This preserves the existing\n+  registered MUL latency, slow-M handshake, stall behavior, RVFI operands, and\n+  nret=1 retirement contract, but should remove a 32-bit M-result mux level\n+  from the hot non-M EX path and modestly improve Tang Nano Fmax.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Separate the fast ALU/jump-link EX/MEM result path from MUL and slow M result-valid commit paths, preserving existing M handshakes and RVFI operand latching.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r9s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/c