{"type":"text","timestamp":1778616701923,"sessionID":"ses_1e2326729ffenk899NFucRvQJZ","part":{"id":"prt_e1dd1108f0011jpeY5M95tB5uj","messageID":"msg_e1dd03bfa001mCuTF4WahwPjyQ","sessionID":"ses_1e2326729ffenk899NFucRvQJZ","type":"text","text":"I’m writing a single structural hypothesis focused on the retirement sidecar: segment the 64-bit RVFI order counter so the FPGA wrapper still sees exact RVFI order, but the core avoids a monolithic 64-bit `+1` carry path.","time":{"start":1778616701071,"end":1778616701922},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0042d8a79bfa9e9d016a03897cf5108194a20e322b6b38a345","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778616705634,"sessionID":"ses_1e2326729ffenk899NFucRvQJZ","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_Dq5rXGoZMWfSlBtBcm9Wng4V","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r13s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r13s1\n+title: \"Segment RVFI order counter\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The FPGA Fmax wrapper deliberately XOR-reduces all RVFI outputs, so the\n+  retirement sidecar remains live in timing even though it does not affect\n+  CoreMark execution. The current core increments rvfi_order with a single\n+  64-bit +1 operation on every retirement, creating a wide carry path in a\n+  design where recent useful gains came from removing or retiming hot cones\n+  without adding prediction, buffering, or bypass machinery.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the monolithic rvfi_order_q <= rvfi_order_q + 64'd1 update with an\n+  exact segmented retirement-order generator, for example four 16-bit limbs\n+  or two 32-bit halves with explicit carry enables. The channel-0 RVFI output\n+  still presents the full concatenated 64-bit order before increment, reset\n+  still starts at zero, and each valid retirement still advances the order by\n+  exactly one with no gaps or duplicates. This should shorten the retirement\n+  counter register-to-register path and reduce RVFI-side routing pressure in\n+  the Fmax wrapper while leaving the pipeline, CoreMark cycle count, nret=1\n+  port contract, trap behavior, and memory semantics unchanged.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Retire through an exact segmented 64-bit RVFI order counter instead of a single wide +1 adder, preserving channel-0 order semantics and all existing RVFI fields.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r13s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r13s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r13s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r13s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,26 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r13s1\n+title: \"Segment RVFI order counter\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The FPGA Fmax wrapper deliberately XOR-reduces all RVFI outputs, so the\n+  retirement sidecar remains live in timing even though it does not affect\n+  CoreMark execution. The current core increments rvfi_order with a single\n+  64-bit +1 operation on every retirement, creating a wide carry path in a\n+  design where recent useful gains came from removing or retiming hot cones\n+  without adding prediction, buffering, or bypass machinery.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the monolithic rvfi_order_q <= rvfi_order_q + 64'd1 update with an\n+  exact segmented retirement-order generator, for example four 16-bit limbs\n+  or two 32-bit halves with explicit carry enables. The channel-0 RVFI output\n+  still presents the full concatenated 64-bit order before increment, reset\n+  still starts at zero, and each valid retirement still advances the order by\n+  exactly one with no gaps or duplicates. This should shorten the retirement\n+  counter register-to-register path and reduce RVFI-side routing pressure in\n+  the Fmax wrapper while leaving the pipeline, CoreMark cycle count, nret=1\n+  port contract, trap behavior, and memory semantics unchanged.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Retire through an exact segmented 64-bit RVFI order counter instead of a single wide +1 adder, preserving channel-0 order semantics and all existing RVFI fields.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r13s1.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r13s1.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r13s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r13s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r13s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,26 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r13s1\n+title: \"Segment RVFI order counter\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The FPGA Fmax wrapper deliberately XOR-reduces all RVFI outputs, so the\n+  retirement sidecar remains live in timing even though it does not affect\n+  CoreMark execution. The current core increments rvfi_order with a single\n+  64-bit +1 operation on every retirement, creating a wide carry path in a\n+  design where recent useful gains came from removing or retiming hot cones\n+  without adding prediction, buffering, or bypass machinery.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the monolithic rvfi_order_q <= rvfi_order_q + 64'd1 update with an\n+  exact segmented retirement-order generator, for example four 16-bit limbs\n+  or two 32-bit halves with explicit carry enables. The channel-0 RVFI output\n+  still presents the full concatenated 64-bit order before increment, reset\n+  still starts at zero, and each valid retirement still advances the order by\n+  exactly one with no gaps or duplicates. This should shorten the retirement\n+  counter regis