{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778617803982,"sessionID":"ses_1e21fea04ffeeXeaM6yHFemfp4","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_Oy4huG4uzwFNeXezleXNdA9M","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r14s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r14s1\n+title: \"Registered RVFI sidecar\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The FPGA benchmark wrapper keeps the RVFI outputs live by reducing them, so\n+  retirement metadata can still influence Fmax even though it does not drive\n+  execution. Prior structural wins came from removing load from hot EX/RV32M\n+  cones, while prediction, buffering, MEM bypassing, store buffering, and\n+  regfile rewrites repeatedly lost more timing than they recovered. A narrow\n+  remaining structural target is the direct fanout from MEM/WB and the live WB\n+  result mux into the wide RVFI output bus.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a one-cycle RVFI sidecar register stage in rtl/core.sv. Capture the\n+  current MEM/WB retirement fields, final rd_wdata, memory masks/data, trap\n+  state, and order into dedicated RVFI output flops, then drive io_rvfi_*_0 only\n+  from those flops while incrementing rvfi_order on sidecar-valid retirements.\n+  The architectural trace is delayed by one cycle but remains strictly in order\n+  with the same nret=1 channel-0 contract and the same trap, memory, and rd\n+  values. This should reduce MEM/WB register fanout into the FPGA wrapper's\n+  RVFI XOR cone and improve placement/timing without changing IF, EX, MEM,\n+  dmem-stall, branch, or CoreMark IPC behavior.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Add a registered RVFI sidecar/output stage driven from MEM/WB and wb_w_data, preserving nret=1 channel-0 fields and strict order semantics.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r14s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r14s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r14s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r14s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,27 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r14s1\n+title: \"Registered RVFI sidecar\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The FPGA benchmark wrapper keeps the RVFI outputs live by reducing them, so\n+  retirement metadata can still influence Fmax even though it does not drive\n+  execution. Prior structural wins came from removing load from hot EX/RV32M\n+  cones, while prediction, buffering, MEM bypassing, store buffering, and\n+  regfile rewrites repeatedly lost more timing than they recovered. A narrow\n+  remaining structural target is the direct fanout from MEM/WB and the live WB\n+  result mux into the wide RVFI output bus.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a one-cycle RVFI sidecar register stage in rtl/core.sv. Capture the\n+  current MEM/WB retirement fields, final rd_wdata, memory masks/data, trap\n+  state, and order into dedicated RVFI output flops, then drive io_rvfi_*_0 only\n+  from those flops while incrementing rvfi_order on sidecar-valid retirements.\n+  The architectural trace is delayed by one cycle but remains strictly in order\n+  with the same nret=1 channel-0 contract and the same trap, memory, and rd\n+  values. This should reduce MEM/WB register fanout into the FPGA wrapper's\n+  RVFI XOR cone and improve placement/timing without changing IF, EX, MEM,\n+  dmem-stall, branch, or CoreMark IPC behavior.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Add a registered RVFI sidecar/output stage driven from MEM/WB and wb_w_data, preserving nret=1 channel-0 fields and strict order semantics.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r14s1.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r14s1.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r14s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r14s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r14s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,27 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r14s1\n+title: \"Registered RVFI sidecar\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The FPGA benchmark wrapper keeps the RVFI outputs live by reducing them, so\n+  retirement metadata can still influence Fmax even though it does not drive\n+  execution. Prior structural wins came from removing load from hot EX/RV32M\n+  cones, while prediction, buffering, MEM bypassing, store buffering, and\n+  regfile rewrites repeatedly lost more timing than they recovered. A narrow\n+  remaining structural target is the direct fanout from MEM/WB and the live WB\n+  result mux into the wide RVFI output bus.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a one-cycle RVFI sidecar register stage in rtl/core.sv. Capture the\n+  current MEM/WB retirement fields, final rd_wdata, memory masks/data, trap\n+  state, and order into dedicated RVFI output flops, then drive io_rvfi_*_0 only\n+  from those flops while incrementing rvfi_order on sidecar-valid retirements.\n+  The architectural trace is delayed by one cycle but remains strictly in order\n+  with the same nret=1 channel-0 contract and the same trap, memory, and rd\n+  values. This should reduce MEM/WB register fanout into the FPGA wrapper's\n+  RVFI XOR cone and improve placement/timing without changing IF, EX, MEM,\n+  dmem-stall, branch, or CoreMark IPC behavior.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Add a registered RVFI sidecar/output stage driven from MEM/WB and wb_w_data, preserving nret=1 channel-0 fields and strict order semantics.\"\n","additions":27,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r14s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778617803975,"end":1778617803980}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_039e4da6627f9119016a038dc3b0708194a25b29e52e12b17a"}},"id":"prt_e1de1c50a001Qvw2tvSCsmKy4Y","sessionID":"ses_1e21fea04ffeeXeaM6yHFemfp4","messageID":"msg_e1de198e1001np1iCUX7dxh0rG"}}
