{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778617834754,"sessionID":"ses_1e21fea04ffeeXeaM6yHFemfp4","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_B0QUOWTWSl1KgQGr7gUWtpDy","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r14s1.yaml","offset":1,"limit":40},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r14s1.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260512-002-r14s1\n2: title: \"Registered RVFI sidecar\"\n3: category: structural\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The FPGA benchmark wrapper keeps the RVFI outputs live by reducing them, so\n6:   retirement metadata can still influence Fmax even though it does not drive\n7:   execution. Prior structural wins came from removing load from hot EX/RV32M\n8:   cones, while prediction, buffering, MEM bypassing, store buffering, and\n9:   regfile rewrites repeatedly lost more timing than they recovered. A narrow\n10:   remaining structural target is the direct fanout from MEM/WB and the live WB\n11:   result mux into the wide RVFI output bus.\n12: hypothesis: |\n13:   Add a one-cycle RVFI sidecar register stage in rtl/core.sv. Capture the\n14:   current MEM/WB retirement fields, final rd_wdata, memory masks/data, trap\n15:   state, and order into dedicated RVFI output flops, then drive io_rvfi_*_0 only\n16:   from those flops while incrementing rvfi_order when a MEM/WB retirement is\n17:   accepted into the sidecar.\n18:   The architectural trace is delayed by one cycle but remains strictly in order\n19:   with the same nret=1 channel-0 contract and the same trap, memory, and rd\n20:   values. This should reduce MEM/WB register fanout into the FPGA wrapper's\n21:   RVFI XOR cone and improve placement/timing without changing IF, EX, MEM,\n22:   dmem-stall, branch, or CoreMark IPC behavior.\n23: expected_impact:\n24:   fitness_delta_pct: 2\n25:   confidence: medium\n26: changes:\n27:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n28:     description: \"Add a registered RVFI sidecar/output stage driven from MEM/WB and wb_w_data, preserving nret=1 channel-0 fields and strict order semantics.\"\n\n(End of file - total 28 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260512-002-r14s1\ntitle: \"Registered RVFI sidecar\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The FPGA benchmark wrapper keeps the RVFI outputs live by reducing them, so\n  retirement metadata can still influence Fmax even though it does not drive\n  execution. Prior structural wins came from removing load from hot EX/RV32M\n  cones, while prediction, buffering, MEM bypassing, store buffering, and\n  regfile rewrites repeatedly lost more timing than they recovered. A narrow\n  remaining structural target is the direct fanout from MEM/WB and the live WB\n  result mux into the wide RVFI output bus.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a one-cycle RVFI sidecar register stage in rtl/core.sv. Capture the\n  current MEM/WB retirement fields, final rd_wdata, memory masks/data, trap\n  state, and order into dedicated RVFI output flops, then drive io_rvfi_*_0 only\n  from those flops while incrementing rvfi_order when a MEM/WB retirement is\n  accepted into the sidecar.\n  The architectural trace is delayed by one cycle but remains strictly in order\n  with the same nret=1 channel-0 contract and the same trap, memory, and rd\n  values. This should reduce MEM/WB register fanout into the FPGA wrapper's","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r14s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778617834751,"end":1778617834754}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0e2bae845ac52add016a038de9671481968ebc34a23a42849d"}},"id":"prt_e1de2582c001mkW3uQ5ZuioHVZ","sessionID":"ses_1e21fea04ffeeXeaM6yHFemfp4","messageID":"msg_e1de24ecd001e6smm4ZJHsn3B1"}}
