/core.sv\n26:     description: \"Wire a MEM-stage load bypass value/tag/valid path from mem_stage into the EX forwarding network while preserving the nret=1 RVFI port contract.\"\n27:   - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n28:     description: \"Expose the aligned and sign/zero-extended load result as a bypassable value only when the load is valid, aligned, and not suppressed by a trap.\"\n29:   - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n30:     description: \"Add a MEM-load forwarding input and operand mux selection so dependent ALU, branch, store-data, and JALR operands can consume a just-loaded value.\"\n31:   - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n32:     description: \"Prioritize MEM-stage load-data forwarding for EX source operands before falling back to EX/MEM ALU and MEM/WB writeback forwarding.\"\n33:   - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n34:     description: \"Relax the unconditional load-use bubble so it only stalls when the pending load cannot be bypassed, such as during dmem backpressure.\"\n\n(End of file - total 34 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260512-002-r3s1\ntitle: \"MEM-to-EX load-use bypass\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The current five-stage pipeline always inserts a bubble when an instruction\n  consumes the destination of the immediately preceding load. That is safe but\n  pessimistic for the zero-wait or ready dmem cycles that dominate the FPGA and\n  random-stall CoreMark runs: the load value is already formed in MEM while the\n  dependent instruction would be in EX. Previous frontend structural work lost\n  too much Fmax, so the better IPC target is a local backend bypass that leaves\n  IF next-PC timing untouched.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a MEM-stage load-data bypass into the EX operand forwarding network and\n  change load-use hazard handling so the dependent instruction stalls only when\n  the load is actually waiting on dmem or cannot produce a valid value. The MEM\n  stage should expose the sign/zero-extended load result plus a valid rd tag;\n  EX should select that value ahead of the older MEM/WB path for matching rs1 or\n  rs2 operands. This should remove common one-cycle load-use bubbles in\n  CoreMark while preserving the existing single-retire RVFI contract and keeping\n  branch prediction/front-end timing unchanged.","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r3s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778598733653,"end":1778598733656}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_06dadc41a91bbe1e016a03434bb87c8197ac025425b34f7d13"}},"id":"prt_e1cbee025001apsSuiBWLiw2qE","sessionID":"ses_1e3435392ffeBisIBxlvhvK74c","messageID":"msg_e1cbec922001VgR1al9IKUjsju"}}
