{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778601604095,"sessionID":"ses_1e3175243ffehaPV1OwgL5rM1c","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_LeO2IrUYzj45Vg9yFUgZyavx","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r5s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r5s1\n+title: \"Register WB forwarding data\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The r4 structural win registered forwarding selects, which suggests the EX\n+  operand cone is still timing-sensitive after the slow RV32M work was moved\n+  off the common path. MEM/WB forwarding still feeds EX through the live WB\n+  write-data mux, so a dependent instruction forwarded from WB carries\n+  mem_to_reg selection into the EX operand mux, ALU, and one-cycle MUL path.\n+  That mux is small, but it sits on the hottest every-cycle datapath and does\n+  not buy CoreMark any IPC.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a registered final writeback value at the MEM/WB boundary and use it for\n+  the regfile write port, RVFI rd_wdata, and MEM/WB-to-EX forwarding. MEM still\n+  computes load extension and ALU-vs-load selection before the MEM/WB flop; EX\n+  then sees only a registered 32-bit forwarding value rather than the live\n+  WB-stage result mux. This preserves the five-stage retirement point, load-use\n+  bubble policy, dmem hold semantics, and nret=1 RVFI contract while shortening\n+  the post-r4 EX operand path with no intentional cycle-count change.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add a final writeback-data field to mem_wb_t so the MEM/WB boundary carries the value used for writes and forwarding.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Compute and register the final WB data alongside existing read_data and alu_result fields, retaining it across hold_wb stalls.\"\n+  - file: rtl/wb_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Drive w_data from the registered MEM/WB value instead of recomputing the mem_to_reg mux in the WB-stage combinational path.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r5s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r5s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r5s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r5s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,29 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r5s1\n+title: \"Register WB forwarding data\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The r4 structural win registered forwarding selects, which suggests the EX\n+  operand cone is still timing-sensitive after the slow RV32M work was moved\n+  off the common path. MEM/WB forwarding still feeds EX through the live WB\n+  write-data mux, so a dependent instruction forwarded from WB carries\n+  mem_to_reg selection into the EX operand mux, ALU, and one-cycle MUL path.\n+  That mux is small, but it sits on the hottest every-cycle datapath and does\n+  not buy CoreMark any IPC.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a registered final writeback value at the MEM/WB boundary and use it for\n+  the regfile write port, RVFI rd_wdata, and MEM/WB-to-EX forwarding. MEM still\n+  computes load extension and ALU-vs-load selection before the MEM/WB flop; EX\n+  then sees only a registered 32-bit forwarding value rather than the live\n+  WB-stage result mux. This preserves the five-stage retirement point, load-use\n+  bubble policy, dmem hold semantics, and nret=1 RVFI contract while shortening\n+  the post-r4 EX operand path with no intentional cycle-count change.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delt