{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778603435092,"sessionID":"ses_1e2fed7abffeL4YF6oJ9GhlF0p","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_LCj13gZ7ELbPCNfwhzzkWvCq","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","offset":12,"limit":1},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n12: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"Register forwarding selects\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"Recent structural IPC attempts added frontend/backend muxing and lost more Fmax than they recovered in cycles. The remaining attractive structural target is the EX operand path itself: live rd/rs compare and priority-select logic currently feeds the ALU and low-half MUL muxes every cycle. Retiming those decisions into the ID/EX register should shorten the hot EX cone without changing branch prediction, load-use behavior, or the nret=1 RVFI contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent structural IPC attempts added frontend/backend muxing and lost more Fmax than they recovered in cycles. The remaining attractive structural target is the EX operand path itself: live rd/rs compare and priority-select logic currently feeds the ALU and low-half MUL muxes every cycle. Retiming those decisions into the ID/EX register should shorten the hot EX cone without changing branch prediction, load-use behavior, or the nret=1 RVFI contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Compute the forwarding source for the instruction while it is still in decode, then carry two registered forwarding-select fields in id_ex_t. Decode can compare the IF/ID rs addresses against the current ID/EX producer, which will be EX/MEM next cycle, and the current EX/MEM producer, which will be MEM/WB next cycle. The existing load-use bubble remains in place, so a load immediately ahead is not treated as an EX/MEM-forwardable producer. EX then uses only the registered select bits plus the existing forwarded data buses, removing the live comparator/priority network from the ALU and one-cycle MUL timing path while preserving identical IPC and stall semantics.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add rs1/rs2 forwarding-select fields to the ID/EX pipeline bundle so forwarding decisions are registered with the instruction.\"... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n\n(Showing lines 12-12 of 16. Use offset=13 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"Register forwarding selects\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"Recent structural IPC attempts added frontend/backend muxing and lost more Fmax than they recovered in cycles. The remaining attractive structural target is the EX operand path itself: live rd/rs compare and priority-select logic currently feeds the ALU and low-half MUL muxes every cycle. Retiming those decisions into the ID/EX register should shorten the hot EX cone without changing branch prediction, load-use behavior, or the nret=1 RVFI contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent structural IPC attempts added frontend/backend muxing and lost more Fmax than they recovered in cycles. The remaining attractive structural target is the EX operand path itself: live rd/rs compare and priority-select logic currently feeds the ALU and low-half MUL muxes every cycle. Retiming those decisions into the ID/EX register should shorten the hot EX cone without changing branch prediction, load-use behavior, or the nret=1 RVFI contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Compute the forwarding source for the instruction while it is still in decode, then carry two registered forwarding-select fields in id_ex_t. Decode can compare the IF/ID rs addresses against the current ID/EX producer, which will be EX/MEM next cycle, and the current EX/MEM producer, which will be MEM/WB next cycle. The existing load-use bubble remains in place, so a load immediately ahead is not treated as an EX/MEM-forwardable producer. EX then uses only the registered select bits plus the existing forwarded data buses, removing the live comparator/priority network from the ALU and one-cycle MUL timing path while preserving identical IPC and stall semantics.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add rs1/rs2 forwarding-select fields to the ID/EX pipeline bundle so forwarding decisions are registered with the instruction.\"... (line truncated to 2000 chars)","truncated":true,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","time":{"start":1778603435079,"end":1778603435092}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_06c36b8975795c5b016a0355a90fb88196b92e162a54539843"}},"id":"prt_e1d069cd60014rwCiDi4oXx7jI","sessionID":"ses_1e2fed7abffeL4YF6oJ9GhlF0p","messageID":"msg_e1d0579a7001v2cK7Qwht82Qbt"}}
