{"type":"text","timestamp":1778604790546,"sessionID":"ses_1e2e9e654ffeMK1yIcOvcSmUMJ","part":{"id":"prt_e1d1b4b4d001HVc5fsk2sbn2U1","messageID":"msg_e1d1b0711001U0dDMOxLqZ7gUE","sessionID":"ses_1e2e9e654ffeMK1yIcOvcSmUMJ","type":"text","text":"I’m writing a structural hypothesis around the register file: remove the non-architectural full-register reset so synthesis can infer duplicated distributed-RAM read banks instead of a reset-heavy flop/mux array, preserving x0 and write-first behavior.","time":{"start":1778604788557,"end":1778604790545},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_01c2102885314058016a035af478e48197855f27e8892d0768","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778604808609,"sessionID":"ses_1e2e9e654ffeMK1yIcOvcSmUMJ","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_nnnoAb7TPK8DjxKbATkRqRJc","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r7s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r7s1\n+title: \"LUTRAM-backed unreset regfile\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  Recent structural attempts that added frontend prediction, fetch buffering,\n+  MEM bypassing, or extra WB state regressed because they added muxing and\n+  control to already sensitive paths. The current register file is still a\n+  32x32 reset-cleared, two-read flop array with write-first bypass muxes; that\n+  reset loop and wide read muxing consume many FFs and routing resources even\n+  though RV32I only requires x0 to be zero after reset. Removing the\n+  non-architectural full-register reset is a localized structural change with\n+  no intended CoreMark cycle-count impact.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Recode rtl/reg_file.sv as an unreset, duplicated two-read-bank register file\n+  suitable for distributed LUT RAM inference. Keep both banks written together,\n+  keep x0 hardwired to zero, and retain the explicit same-cycle write-first\n+  bypass so the existing decode/forwarding contract is unchanged. With reset\n+  removed from the 31 writable registers, yosys/nextpnr should have less reset\n+  fanout, fewer flop-based read muxes, and better packing/routing around the\n+  decode-to-ID/EX path, improving Fmax without changing IPC, RVFI ordering, or\n+  any hard invariant.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/reg_file.sv\n+    description: \"Replace the reset-cleared flop array with unreset duplicated read banks that preserve x0 hardwiring and write-first bypass semantics for LUTRAM-friendly synthesis.\"\n+  - file: test/test_reg_file.py\n+    description: \"Update the regfile unit test to stop asserting non-architectural reset clearing of x1-x31 while continuing to check x0, writes, two read ports, and write-first bypass.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r7s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r7s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r7s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r7s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,29 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r7s1\n+title: \"LUTRAM-backed unreset regfile\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  Recent structural attempts that added frontend prediction, fetch buffering,\n+  MEM bypassing, or extra WB state regressed because they added muxing and\n+  control to already sensitive paths. The current register file is still a\n+  32x32 reset-cleared, two-read flop array with write-first bypass muxes; that\n+  reset loop and wide read muxing consume many FFs and routing resources even\n+  though RV32I only requires x0 to be zero after reset. Removing the\n+  non-architectural full-register reset is a localized structural change with\n+  no intended CoreMark cycle-count impact.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Recode rtl/reg_file.sv as an unreset, duplicated two-read-bank register file\n+  suitable for distributed LUT RAM inference. Keep both banks written together,\n+  keep x0 hardwired to zero, and retain the explicit same-cycle write-first\n+  bypass so the existing decode/forwarding contract is unchanged. With reset\n+  removed from the 31 writable registers, yosys/nextpnr should have less reset\n+  fanout, fewer flop-based read muxes, and better pack