{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778606538684,"sessionID":"ses_1e2ca6184ffes01WuuUxF8Lsy5","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_ax5ePMnS4NpLyDb3puAiP6SW","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/LESSONS.md","offset":1,"limit":300},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/LESSONS.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r1s0 (regression, +23.72%): Single-cycle RV32M datapath sharing can worsen FPGA timing because sign-select muxing, 33x33 multiply width, and quotient-derived remainder logic stay in the EX output cone despite reducing source-level arithmetic duplication.\n2: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r1s1 (improvement, +30.41%): Keeping only low-half MUL on the single-cycle EX path while moving rare high-half multiply and DIV/REM ops into a stalling m_unit removes slow RV32M mux cones from CoreMark's hot path and materially improves Fmax.\n3: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r1s2 (regression, +13.57%): Static backward/JAL prediction can lose more to the IF-stage next-PC critical cone (immediate decode, PC+target add, alignment muxing) than it saves in CoreMark EX redirect flushes.\n4: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r2s0 (regression, -1.23%): Manual 16-bit partial-product decomposition for MUL[31:0] can regress FPGA fitness because it forces three multiplies and cross-product adders into the EX cone instead of letting synthesis trim a single inferred `a * b`.\n5: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r2s1 (regression, -16.67%): Elastic IF buffering can lose on this CoreMark target when buffer valid/data/PC muxing and queue control add more frontend timing cost than random imem-stall overlap can repay.\n6: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r2s2 (regression, -5.44%): EX-trained tiny BTB prediction still regressed CoreMark; even without IF target recompute, the valid/tag/counter/target array read plus compare and next-PC mux added more fetch-side cost than saved redirect bubbles.\n7: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r3s0 (improvement, +3.22%): Splitting slow RV32M finalization into an unsigned last iteration plus a finish cycle can improve Fmax because sign correction and result selection leave the iterative m_unit carry/mux cone while CoreMark rarely pays the added latency.\n8: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r3s1 (regression, -30.29%): MEM-to-EX load-use bypass regressed because dmem-ready/load-extension validity and extra forwarding wait muxes added more backend timing/control cost than saved CoreMark's single-cycle load-use bubbles.\n9: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r3s2 (regression, -35.63%): Even a single-entry EX-trained backward-loop predictor regressed CoreMark, implying the IF exact-PC hit compare/next-PC mux plus ID/EX `pred_pc` redirect-suppression compare costs more timing/control than the saved taken-loop flushes.\n10: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r4s0 (regression, -1.03%): Replacing MEM byte-lane shifts with explicit case muxes can slightly regress FPGA fitness because synthesis already handles small lane shifts well and manual lane decode/muxing stays on every load/store path.\n11: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r4s1 (improvement, +1.58%): Registering decode-time forwarding selects gives a small fitness gain by moving rd/rs compare and priority logic out of the EX ALU/MUL operand cone, as long as load-use bubbles and non-forwardable load/jump cases are preserved.\n12: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r4s2 (regression, -3.19%): Even canonical-ret-only RAS prediction can regress CoreMark because the IF `imem_data` return compare, RAS top/index read, and next-PC mux cost more timing than saved JALR redirect bubbles.\n13: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r5s0 (regression, -5.72%): Source-use-qualified load-use detection regressed because CoreMark's false load-use bubbles are cheaper than adding IF/ID opcode source decode and qualified hazard control to the stall path.\n14: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r5s1 (regression, -1.42%): Registering MEM/WB writeback data regressed slightly because the WB result mux was not the binding EX forwarding path, while the extra 32-bit MEM/WB field/register increased backend state/fanout without changing CoreMark IPC.\n15: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r5s2 (regression, -47.75%): Decode-stage direct-JAL prediction can be worse than EX redirect because it creates an ID decode/imm-add to IF next-PC feedback path plus EX redirect-suppression and forwarding exceptions for bubbles CoreMark does not repay.\n16: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r6s0 (regression, -2.27%): Precomputing `pc+4` and `pc+imm` into ID/EX can regress when the extra 64 bits of pipeline state and ID-side adders cost more routing/timing than removing EX PC adders and the AUIPC ALU-input mux saves.\n17: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r6s1 (regression, -10.63%): Pruning seemingly dead EX/MEM `branch_taken`/`branch_target` and `ctrl.is_lui` sidebands can hurt QoR because those fields were not the timing bottleneck and RTL reshaping perturbed synthesis without improving IPC.\n18: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r6s2 (regression, -23.60%): Removing loop predictor tag/PC compares was still not enough for CoreMark; countdown predictor state, IF next-PC muxing, and ID/EX prediction-recovery metadata kept the control path cost above the saved loop-redirect bubbles.\n19: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r7s0 (regression, -10.54%): Manually sharing EX branch compare flags can hurt QoR because synthesis already optimizes equality/range inversions, while the explicit `cmp_ltu`/sign-correction flag network adds fanout and muxing on the branch redirect path.\n20: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r7s1 (regression, -3.68%): Duplicating the regfile into unreset LUTRAM read banks can cost more write fanout and LUT/read-mux routing than it saves in resettable flops, so the reset-cleared flop regfile was not the binding CoreMark timing/area path.\n21: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r7s2 (regression, -31.57%): Registering a one-fetch-ahead loop predictor still regressed CoreMark because the IF next-PC mux, `pred_taken`/`pred_target` sidebands, and EX prediction-mismatch recovery compare outweighed saved backward-branch redirects.\n\n(End of file - total 21 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r1s0 (regression, +23.72%): Single-cycle RV32M datapath sharing can worsen FPGA timing because sign-select muxing, 33x33 multiply width, and quotient-derived remainder logic stay in the EX output cone despite reducing source-level arithmetic duplication.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r1s1 (improvement, +30.41%): Keeping only low-half MUL on the single-cycle EX path while moving rare high-half multiply and DIV/REM ops into a stalling m_unit removes slow RV32M mux cones from CoreMark's hot path and materially improves Fmax.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r1s2 (regression, +13.57%): Static backward/JAL prediction can lose more to the IF-stage next-PC critical cone (immediate decode, PC+target add, alignment muxing) than it saves in CoreMark EX redirect flushes.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r2s0 (regression, -1.23%): Manual 16-bit partial-product decomposition for MUL[31:0] can regress FPGA fitness because it forces three multiplies and cross-product adders into the EX cone instead of letting synthesis trim a single inferred `a * b`.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r2s1 (regression, -16.67%): Elastic IF buffering can lose on this CoreMark target when buffer valid/data/PC muxing and queue control add more frontend timing cost than random imem-stall overlap can repay.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r2s2 (regression, -5.44%): EX-trained tiny BTB prediction still regressed CoreMark; even without IF target recompute, the valid/tag/counter/target array read plus compare and next-PC mux added more fetch-side cost than saved redirect bubbles.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r3s0 (improvement, +3.22%): Splitting slow RV32M finalization into an unsigned last iteration plus a finish cycle can improve Fmax because sign correction and result selection leave the iterative m_unit carry/mux cone while CoreMark rarely pays the added latency.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r3s1 (regression, -30.29%): MEM-to-EX load-use bypass regressed because dmem-ready/load-extension validity and extra forwarding wait muxes added more backend timing/control cost than saved CoreMark's single-cycle load-use bubbles.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r3s2 (regression, -35.63%): Even a single-entry EX-trained backward-loop predictor regressed CoreMark, implying the IF exact-PC hit compare/next-PC mux plus ID/EX `pred_pc` redirect-suppression compare costs more timing/control than the saved taken-loop flushes.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r4s0 (regression, -1.03%): Replacing MEM byte-lane shifts with explicit case muxes can slightly regress FPGA fitness because synthesis already handles small lane shifts well and manual lane decode/muxing stays on every load/store path.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r4s1 (improvement, +1.58%): Registering decode-time forwarding selects gives a small fitness gain by moving rd/rs compare and priority logic out of the EX ALU/MUL operand cone, as long as load-use bubbles and non-forwardable load/jump cases are preserved.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r4s2 (regression, -3.19%): Even canonical-ret-only RAS prediction can regress CoreMark because the IF `imem_data` return compare, RAS top/index read, and next-PC mux cost more timing than saved JALR redirect bubbles.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r5s0 (regression, -5.72%): Source-use-qualified load-use detection regressed because CoreMark's false load-use bubbles are cheaper than adding IF/ID opcode source decode and qualified hazard control to the stall path.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r5s1 (regression, -1.42%): Registering MEM/WB writeback data regressed slightly because the WB result mux was not the binding EX forwarding path, while the extra 32-bit MEM/WB field/register increased backend state/fanout without changing CoreMark IPC.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r5s2 (regression, -47.75%): Decode-stage direct-JAL prediction can be worse than EX redirect because it creates an ID decode/imm-add to IF next-PC feedback path plus EX redirect-suppression and forwarding exceptions for bubbles CoreMark does not repay.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r6s0 (regression, -2.27%): Precomputing `pc+4` and `pc+imm` into ID/EX can regress when the extra 64 bits of pipeline state and ID-side adders cost more routing/timing than removing EX PC adders and the AUIPC ALU-input mux saves.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r6s1 (regression, -10.63%): Pruning seemingly dead EX/MEM `branch_taken`/`branch_target` and `ctrl.is_lui` sidebands can hurt QoR because those fields were not the timing bottleneck and RTL reshaping perturbed synthesis without improving IPC.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r6s2 (regression, -23.60%): Removing loop predictor tag/PC compares was still not enough for CoreMark; countdown predictor state, IF next-PC muxing, and ID/EX prediction-recovery metadata kept the control path cost above the saved loop-redirect bubbles.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r7s0 (regression, -10.54%): Manually sharing EX branch compare flags can hurt QoR because synthesis already optimizes equality/range inversions, while the explicit `cmp_ltu`/sign-correction flag network adds fanout and muxing on the branch redirect path.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r7s1 (regression, -3.68%): Duplicating the regfile into unreset LUTRAM read banks can cost more write fanout and LUT/read-mux routing than it saves in resettable flops, so the reset-cleared flop regfile was not the binding CoreMark timing/area path.","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/LESSONS.md","time":{"start":1778606538673,"end":1778606538683}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_03bc3aca1329ba24016a0361ca832c81939b63ec7a61247cdc"}},"id":"prt_e1d35ff920017kbBm86Fc4cY3g","sessionID":"ses_1e2ca6184ffes01WuuUxF8Lsy5","messageID":"msg_e1d359eeb001pPTiFjiTWGhI40"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778606538710,"sessionID":"ses_1e2ca6184ffes01WuuUxF8Lsy5","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_dzkGsZum0cxMqsp6Ev4qyGPA","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"\"category\"\\s*:\\s*\"structural\"|category: structural|structural","path":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments","include":"log.jsonl"},"output":"Found 7 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 3: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Decouple slow RV32M ops from EX\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current EX stage routes every instruction through a fully combinational\\nRV32IM ALU that includes parallel high-half multipliers plus DIV/REM logic.\\nCoreMark's timed region is dominated by integer ALU, load/store, branch, and\\nlow-half MUL work, while DIV/REM and high-half multiply are either absent or\\nrare. Keeping those slow operators on the single-cycle EX timing path likely\\ndepresses Fmax without improving CoreMark IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current EX stage routes every instruction through a fully combinational\\nRV32IM ALU that includes parallel high-half multipliers plus DIV/REM logic.\\nCoreMark's timed region is dominated by integer ALU, load/store, branch, and\\nlow-half MUL work, while DIV/REM and high-half multiply are either absent or\\nrare. Keeping those slow operators on the single-cycle EX timing path likely\\ndepresses Fmax without improving CoreMark IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure EX into a fast single-cycle I-ALU plus a separate RV32M slow-unit.\\nKeep ALU_MUL's low-half multiply on a one-cycle fast path for CoreMark, but\\nmove MULH/MULHSU/MULHU and DIV/REM/REMU into a shared multi-cycle unit that\\nstalls the in-order pipeline only while those rare operations are in flight.\\nThis should remove the divider and redundant high-multiply logic from the\\ncommon EX critical path, reduce LUT pressure near the current budget, and\\nraise Fmax with minimal impact on the benchmark instruction stream.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Reduce the combinational ALU to RV32I operations plus the one-cycle MUL low-half fast path; remove DIV/REM and high-half multiply from the common result mux.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Dispatch slow RV32M operations to a separate multi-cycle unit, hold EX state until result_valid, and ...\n  Line 6: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"Elastic IF fetch buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current front end ties instruction fetch directly to decode: when ID is\\nstalled for load-use, dmem backpressure, or a slow M operation, the PC also\\nholds and no useful instruction fetch can be performed. With the tournament\\ncosim injecting about 22 percent random instruction stalls, those missed\\nopportunities turn independent stalls into serialized bubbles. The failed\\nstatic predictor showed that adding next-PC computation in IF is too costly,\\nso the better structural target is decoupling fetch from decode without\\nadding branch-target logic to the IF critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current front end ties instruction fetch directly to decode: when ID is\\nstalled for load-use, dmem backpressure, or a slow M operation, the PC also\\nholds and no useful instruction fetch can be performed. With the tournament\\ncosim injecting about 22 percent random instruction stalls, those missed\\nopportunities turn independent stalls into serialized bubbles. The failed\\nstatic predictor showed that adding next-PC computation in IF is too costly,\\nso the better structural target is decoupling fetch from decode without\\nadding branch-target logic to the IF critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Insert a tiny elastic fetch buffer between IF and ID. The buffer should keep\\nthe existing direct fall-through path when decode is ready, but when ID/EX is\\nstalled it should let IF continue fetching sequential instructions into one\\nor two registered slots until the buffer is full. Decode then consumes from\\nthe buffer before requesting a fresh instruction, hiding later imemReady=0\\ncycles behind earlier load-use, dmem, or slow-M stalls. Redirects flush the\\nbuffer and restart fetch at the resolved target, preserving precise single\\nretirement and the existing RVFI channel-0 contract.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"chang...\n  Line 9: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r3s1\", \"title\": \"MEM-to-EX load-use bypass\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage pipeline always inserts a bubble when an instruction\\nconsumes the destination of the immediately preceding load. That is safe but\\npessimistic for the zero-wait or ready dmem cycles that dominate the FPGA and\\nrandom-stall CoreMark runs: the load value is already formed in MEM while the\\ndependent instruction would be in EX. Previous frontend structural work lost\\ntoo much Fmax, so the better IPC target is a local backend bypass that leaves\\nIF next-PC timing untouched.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage pipeline always inserts a bubble when an instruction\\nconsumes the destination of the immediately preceding load. That is safe but\\npessimistic for the zero-wait or ready dmem cycles that dominate the FPGA and\\nrandom-stall CoreMark runs: the load value is already formed in MEM while the\\ndependent instruction would be in EX. Previous frontend structural work lost\\ntoo much Fmax, so the better IPC target is a local backend bypass that leaves\\nIF next-PC timing untouched.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a MEM-stage load-data bypass into the EX operand forwarding network and\\nchange load-use hazard handling so the dependent instruction stalls only when\\nthe load is actually waiting on dmem or cannot produce a valid value. The MEM\\nstage should expose the sign/zero-extended load result plus a valid rd tag;\\nEX should select that value ahead of the older MEM/WB path for matching rs1 or\\nrs2 operands. This should remove common one-cycle load-use bubbles in\\nCoreMark while preserving the existing single-retire RVFI contract and keeping\\nbranch prediction/front-end timing unchanged.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire a MEM-stage load bypass value/tag/valid path from mem_stage into the EX forwarding network while preserving the nret=1 ...\n  Line 12: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"Register forwarding selects\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"Recent structural IPC attempts added frontend/backend muxing and lost more Fmax than they recovered in cycles. The remaining attractive structural target is the EX operand path itself: live rd/rs compare and priority-select logic currently feeds the ALU and low-half MUL muxes every cycle. Retiming those decisions into the ID/EX register should shorten the hot EX cone without changing branch prediction, load-use behavior, or the nret=1 RVFI contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent structural IPC attempts added frontend/backend muxing and lost more Fmax than they recovered in cycles. The remaining attractive structural target is the EX operand path itself: live rd/rs compare and priority-select logic currently feeds the ALU and low-half MUL muxes every cycle. Retiming those decisions into the ID/EX register should shorten the hot EX cone without changing branch prediction, load-use behavior, or the nret=1 RVFI contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Compute the forwarding source for the instruction while it is still in decode, then carry two registered forwarding-select fields in id_ex_t. Decode can compare the IF/ID rs addresses against the current ID/EX producer, which will be EX/MEM next cycle, and the current EX/MEM producer, which will be MEM/WB next cycle. The existing load-use bubble remains in place, so a load immediately ahead is not treated as an EX/MEM-forwardable producer. EX then uses only the registered select bits plus the existing forwarded data buses, removing the live comparator/priority network from the ALU and one-cycle MUL timing path while preserving identical IPC and stall semantics.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add rs1/rs2 forwarding-select fields to the ID/EX pipeline bundle so forwarding decisions are registered with the instruction.\"...\n  Line 15: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r5s1\", \"title\": \"Register WB forwarding data\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The r4 structural win registered forwarding selects, which suggests the EX\\noperand cone is still timing-sensitive after the slow RV32M work was moved\\noff the common path. MEM/WB forwarding still feeds EX through the live WB\\nwrite-data mux, so a dependent instruction forwarded from WB carries\\nmem_to_reg selection into the EX operand mux, ALU, and one-cycle MUL path.\\nThat mux is small, but it sits on the hottest every-cycle datapath and does\\nnot buy CoreMark any IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The r4 structural win registered forwarding selects, which suggests the EX\\noperand cone is still timing-sensitive after the slow RV32M work was moved\\noff the common path. MEM/WB forwarding still feeds EX through the live WB\\nwrite-data mux, so a dependent instruction forwarded from WB carries\\nmem_to_reg selection into the EX operand mux, ALU, and one-cycle MUL path.\\nThat mux is small, but it sits on the hottest every-cycle datapath and does\\nnot buy CoreMark any IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a registered final writeback value at the MEM/WB boundary and use it for\\nthe regfile write port, RVFI rd_wdata, and MEM/WB-to-EX forwarding. MEM still\\ncomputes load extension and ALU-vs-load selection before the MEM/WB flop; EX\\nthen sees only a registered 32-bit forwarding value rather than the live\\nWB-stage result mux. This preserves the five-stage retirement point, load-use\\nbubble policy, dmem hold semantics, and nret=1 RVFI contract while shortening\\nthe post-r4 EX operand path with no intentional cycle-count change.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a final writeback-data field to mem_wb_t so the MEM/WB boundary carries the value used for writes and forwarding.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute and register the final WB data alongside exi...\n  Line 18: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r6s1\", \"title\": \"Slim unused pipeline sidebands\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"Recent structural wins came from shortening hot pipeline cones without adding\\nnew IPC machinery, while fetch buffers, load bypasses, and predictors lost\\nmore Fmax than they recovered. The current RTL still carries some metadata\\nthat is not consumed after EX, including EX/MEM branch_taken and\\nbranch_target fields plus an is_lui control bit that is redundant with\\nALU_LUI. Those dead sidebands add registers, mux fanout, and routing pressure\\non a design where small retiming changes have already moved fitness.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent structural wins came from shortening hot pipeline cones without adding\\nnew IPC machinery, while fetch buffers, load bypasses, and predictors lost\\nmore Fmax than they recovered. The current RTL still carries some metadata\\nthat is not consumed after EX, including EX/MEM branch_taken and\\nbranch_target fields plus an is_lui control bit that is redundant with\\nALU_LUI. Those dead sidebands add registers, mux fanout, and routing pressure\\non a design where small retiming changes have already moved fitness.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Prune the unused pipeline sidebands rather than changing execution behavior:\\nremove branch_taken and branch_target from ex_mem_t and stop registering them,\\nand remove the dead is_lui control bit from ctrl_t while keeping LUI legality\\nrepresented by ALU_LUI and the existing immediate path. Branch redirect and\\npc_next calculation still use local EX signals in the same cycle, so IPC,\\nstall behavior, traps, and the nret=1 RVFI contract are unchanged. The smaller\\npipeline payload should reduce EX/MEM fanout, backend register count, and\\nnextpnr routing pressure, yielding a modest Fmax-driven fitness gain.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the unused is_lui control bit and dead EX/MEM b...\n  Line 21: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r7s1\", \"title\": \"LUTRAM-backed unreset regfile\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"Recent structural attempts that added frontend prediction, fetch buffering,\\nMEM bypassing, or extra WB state regressed because they added muxing and\\ncontrol to already sensitive paths. The current register file is still a\\n32x32 reset-cleared, two-read flop array with write-first bypass muxes; that\\nreset loop and wide read muxing consume many FFs and routing resources even\\nthough RV32I only requires x0 to be zero after reset. Removing the\\nnon-architectural full-register reset is a localized structural change with\\nno intended CoreMark cycle-count impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent structural attempts that added frontend prediction, fetch buffering,\\nMEM bypassing, or extra WB state regressed because they added muxing and\\ncontrol to already sensitive paths. The current register file is still a\\n32x32 reset-cleared, two-read flop array with write-first bypass muxes; that\\nreset loop and wide read muxing consume many FFs and routing resources even\\nthough RV32I only requires x0 to be zero after reset. Removing the\\nnon-architectural full-register reset is a localized structural change with\\nno intended CoreMark cycle-count impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Recode rtl/reg_file.sv as an unreset, duplicated two-read-bank register file\\nsuitable for distributed LUT RAM inference. Keep both banks written together,\\nkeep x0 hardwired to zero, and retain the explicit same-cycle write-first\\nbypass so the existing decode/forwarding contract is unchanged. With reset\\nremoved from the 31 writable registers, yosys/nextpnr should have less reset\\nfanout, fewer flop-based read muxes, and better packing/routing around the\\ndecode-to-ID/EX path, improving Fmax without changing IPC, RVFI ordering, or\\nany hard invariant.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/reg_file.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the...","metadata":{"matches":7,"truncated":false},"title":"\"category\"\\s*:\\s*\"structural\"|category: structural|structural","time":{"start":1778606538690,"end":1778606538709}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_03bc3aca1329ba24016a0361ca834081939025b3620cf3a258"}},"id":"prt_e1d35ffb8001i2VMHkZGBcYMA1","sessionID":"ses_1e2ca6184ffes01WuuUxF8Lsy5","messageID":"msg_e1d359eeb001pPTiFjiTWGhI40"}}
