{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778608794357,"sessionID":"ses_1e2ab0529ffev4Hn0LxnlMvr5w","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_A1Epz7BoAvzdJXrWhUD6KrZl","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r9s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r9s1\n+title: \"Unified RV32M side unit\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The strongest structural gains so far came from removing RV32M arithmetic from\n+  the common EX-stage ALU cone, culminating in a registered low-half MUL side\n+  path. That latest change improved Fmax, but it left EX with two separate M\n+  side-unit handshakes, two result-valid paths, and a three-way result select for\n+  logic that is only active on M-extension instructions.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Fold the standalone registered low-half MUL path into the existing RV32M side\n+  unit while preserving the one-cycle registered MUL latency and the existing\n+  multi-cycle behavior for MULH/DIV/REM. EX should classify every M-extension\n+  instruction as one side-unit operation, use one start/result_valid/result_ready\n+  handshake, and feed EX/MEM through one registered M result path. This should\n+  keep the r8 MUL timing win, remove duplicate busy/control muxing from EX, and\n+  slightly improve Tang Nano Fmax without changing CoreMark IPC except for the\n+  already-accepted MUL bubble.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Replace the separate mul_unit and slow m_unit dispatch paths with a single M-extension side-unit handshake and one result mux path.\"\n+  - file: rtl/m_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Add ALU_MUL support as a one-cycle registered low-half multiply result, including the RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS substitute expression.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mul_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Remove the standalone low-half MUL side path or leave it unused after EX dispatch is consolidated into m_unit.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r9s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r9s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r9s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r9s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,28 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r9s1\n+title: \"Unified RV32M side unit\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The strongest structural gains so far came from removing RV32M arithmetic from\n+  the common EX-stage ALU cone, culminating in a registered low-half MUL side\n+  path. That latest change improved Fmax, but it left EX with two separate M\n+  side-unit handshakes, two result-valid paths, and a three-way result select for\n+  logic that is only active on M-extension instructions.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Fold the standalone registered low-half MUL path into the existing RV32M side\n+  unit while preserving the one-cycle registered MUL latency and the existing\n+  multi-cycle behavior for MULH/DIV/REM. EX should classify every M-extension\n+  instruction as one side-unit operation, use one start/result_valid/result_ready\n+  handshake, and feed EX/MEM through one registered M result path. This should\n+  keep the r8 MUL timing win, remove duplicate busy/control muxing from EX, and\n+  slightly improve Tang Nano Fmax without changing CoreMark IPC except for the\n+  already-accepted MUL bubble.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Replace the separate mul_unit and slow m_unit disp