{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778610775841,"sessionID":"ses_1e28cc88affe66v0go10HofS0Q","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_6gEPerJ8ftUBil8gTbVU5XF6","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r10s2.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-003-r10s2\n+title: \"Exact trivial-MUL result predictor\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  Prior CoreMark branch predictors repeatedly lost fitness by adding lookup,\n+  target, mux, and recovery logic to the IF next-PC path. The current best\n+  core instead gained by registering low-half MUL, but that makes every MUL\n+  pay an EX hold even when the result is an obvious function of a zero, one,\n+  or minus-one operand. A predictor that classifies only those exact operand\n+  cases can recover some MUL bubbles without touching fetch prediction.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add an exact operand-class result predictor for ALU_MUL inside EX. When a\n+  valid low-half MUL has an operand of 0, 1, or 0xffffffff, bypass the\n+  registered multiplier and emit the known result in the normal EX/MEM commit\n+  cycle; all other MULs continue using the existing mul_unit hold protocol.\n+  This keeps branch prediction out of the sensitive frontend, preserves exact\n+  RV32M semantics with no speculative rollback, and may improve CoreMark\n+  cycles if its matrix/state kernels contain trivial multiplier operands while\n+  keeping the common non-MUL ALU path nearly unchanged.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 1\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add exact zero/one/minus-one ALU_MUL result classification, suppress mul_unit start/EX hold on hits, and preserve existing slow-M and RVFI operand latching behavior.\"\n+  - file: test/test_mul_fastpath.py\n+    description: \"Add cocotb coverage for zero, one, and minus-one MUL fast-path cases, including dependent consumers to guard forwarding and RVFI-visible results.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r10s2.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r10s2.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r10s2.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r10s2.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,27 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-003-r10s2\n+title: \"Exact trivial-MUL result predictor\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  Prior CoreMark branch predictors repeatedly lost fitness by adding lookup,\n+  target, mux, and recovery logic to the IF next-PC path. The current best\n+  core instead gained by registering low-half MUL, but that makes every MUL\n+  pay an EX hold even when the result is an obvious function of a zero, one,\n+  or minus-one operand. A predictor that classifies only those exact operand\n+  cases can recover some MUL bubbles without touching fetch prediction.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add an exact operand-class result predictor for ALU_MUL inside EX. When a\n+  valid low-half MUL has an operand of 0, 1, or 0xffffffff, bypass the\n+  registered multiplier and emit the known result in the normal EX/MEM commit\n+  cycle; all other MULs continue using the existing mul_unit hold protocol.\n+  This keeps branch prediction out of the sensitive frontend, preserves exact\n+  RV32M semantics with no speculative rollback, and may improve CoreMark\n+  cycles if its matrix/state kernels contain trivial multiplier operands while\n+  keeping the common non-MUL ALU path nearly unchanged.\n+expect