{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778616489895,"sessionID":"ses_1e2326672ffeu6SPYP8feizLrS","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_uIjGCyIDl5j9UJbd2TAYbz5n","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"predict|BTB|RAS|branch|return|JAL|loop|replay","path":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","include":"log.jsonl"},"output":"Found 32 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 2: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r1s0\", \"title\": \"Share RV32M ALU datapaths\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The bench core's EX ALU currently computes three 64-bit products plus\\nindependent signed/unsigned divide and remainder expressions before selecting\\none result. Even when CoreMark mostly exercises simple ALU and MUL paths,\\nthose wide arithmetic blocks remain in the EX output cone and add LUT and\\nrouting pressure on the Tang Nano 20K. Reducing redundant arithmetic should\\nimprove median Fmax without adding cycles to the common MUL path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The bench core's EX ALU currently computes three 64-bit products plus\\nindependent signed/unsigned divide and remainder expressions before selecting\\none result. Even when CoreMark mostly exercises simple ALU and MUL paths,\\nthose wide arithmetic blocks remain in the EX output cone and add LUT and\\nrouting pressure on the Tang Nano 20K. Reducing redundant arithmetic should\\nimprove median Fmax without adding cycles to the common MUL path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Rewrite the real RV32M branch of rtl/alu.sv so all multiply variants use one\\nsign-configurable 33x33 product, and all DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU variants share\\nnormalized unsigned quotient/remainder logic with the existing RISC-V\\ndivide-by-zero and overflow fixups. Keep the RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS substitutions\\nequivalent and preserve single-cycle ALU latency, so CoreMark IPC should not\\nregress while the FPGA critical path and LUT/routing pressure improve.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace parallel RV32M multiply/divide expressions with shared sign-normalized combinational datapaths while preserving ALTOPS and RV32M corner-case semantics.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Add or retain focused RV32M corner vectors for MULH/MULHSU/MULHU and DIV/REM divide-by-zero/overflow cases to guard the shared datapath rewrite.\"}]}, \"expected_impact...\n  Line 3: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Decouple slow RV32M ops from EX\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current EX stage routes every instruction through a fully combinational\\nRV32IM ALU that includes parallel high-half multipliers plus DIV/REM logic.\\nCoreMark's timed region is dominated by integer ALU, load/store, branch, and\\nlow-half MUL work, while DIV/REM and high-half multiply are either absent or\\nrare. Keeping those slow operators on the single-cycle EX timing path likely\\ndepresses Fmax without improving CoreMark IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current EX stage routes every instruction through a fully combinational\\nRV32IM ALU that includes parallel high-half multipliers plus DIV/REM logic.\\nCoreMark's timed region is dominated by integer ALU, load/store, branch, and\\nlow-half MUL work, while DIV/REM and high-half multiply are either absent or\\nrare. Keeping those slow operators on the single-cycle EX timing path likely\\ndepresses Fmax without improving CoreMark IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure EX into a fast single-cycle I-ALU plus a separate RV32M slow-unit.\\nKeep ALU_MUL's low-half multiply on a one-cycle fast path for CoreMark, but\\nmove MULH/MULHSU/MULHU and DIV/REM/REMU into a shared multi-cycle unit that\\nstalls the in-order pipeline only while those rare operations are in flight.\\nThis should remove the divider and redundant high-multiply logic from the\\ncommon EX critical path, reduce LUT pressure near the current budget, and\\nraise Fmax with minimal impact on the benchmark instruction stream.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Reduce the combinational ALU to RV32I operations plus the one-cycle MUL low-half fast path; remove DIV/REM and high-half multiply from the common result mux.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Dispatch slow RV32M operations to a separate multi-cycle unit, hold EX state until result_valid, and ...\n  Line 4: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"Static backward-branch next-PC predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core resolves all branches and jumps in EX, so every\\ntaken loop branch or direct jump pays the redirect flush penalty. CoreMark is\\nloop-heavy, and a low-cost predictor that fetches backward branch targets and\\ndirect JAL targets immediately should recover cycles without adding large FPGA\\nstructures or touching the single-retire RVFI contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core resolves all branches and jumps in EX, so every\\ntaken loop branch or direct jump pays the redirect flush penalty. CoreMark is\\nloop-heavy, and a low-cost predictor that fetches backward branch targets and\\ndirect JAL targets immediately should recover cycles without adding large FPGA\\nstructures or touching the single-retire RVFI contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an IF-stage static next-PC predictor: predict JAL taken, predict\\nconditional branches with a negative B-immediate taken, and otherwise predict\\nfall-through. Carry the predicted next PC through IF/ID and ID/EX so EX can\\nredirect only when the resolved architectural next PC differs from the\\nprediction. This should turn the common CoreMark loop-back branch from a\\ntaken-branch flush into a correct-path fetch, while forward exits still pay\\nonly the existing mispredict recovery cost.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicted-next-PC metadata to the IF/ID and ID/EX pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute the static backward-branch/JAL prediction from the fetched instruction and use it for the next PC when not stalled or redirected.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Propagate IF-stage prediction metadata into the ID/EX register alongside the decoded instruction.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compare r...\n  Line 6: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"Elastic IF fetch buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current front end ties instruction fetch directly to decode: when ID is\\nstalled for load-use, dmem backpressure, or a slow M operation, the PC also\\nholds and no useful instruction fetch can be performed. With the tournament\\ncosim injecting about 22 percent random instruction stalls, those missed\\nopportunities turn independent stalls into serialized bubbles. The failed\\nstatic predictor showed that adding next-PC computation in IF is too costly,\\nso the better structural target is decoupling fetch from decode without\\nadding branch-target logic to the IF critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current front end ties instruction fetch directly to decode: when ID is\\nstalled for load-use, dmem backpressure, or a slow M operation, the PC also\\nholds and no useful instruction fetch can be performed. With the tournament\\ncosim injecting about 22 percent random instruction stalls, those missed\\nopportunities turn independent stalls into serialized bubbles. The failed\\nstatic predictor showed that adding next-PC computation in IF is too costly,\\nso the better structural target is decoupling fetch from decode without\\nadding branch-target logic to the IF critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Insert a tiny elastic fetch buffer between IF and ID. The buffer should keep\\nthe existing direct fall-through path when decode is ready, but when ID/EX is\\nstalled it should let IF continue fetching sequential instructions into one\\nor two registered slots until the buffer is full. Decode then consumes from\\nthe buffer before requesting a fresh instruction, hiding later imemReady=0\\ncycles behind earlier load-use, dmem, or slow-M stalls. Redirects flush the\\nbuffer and restart fetch at the resolved target, preserving precise single\\nretirement and the existing RVFI channel-0 contract.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"chang...\n  Line 7: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r2s2\", \"title\": \"EX-trained tiny BTB predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The previous static backward-branch predictor recovered some taken-branch\\ncycles, but it put immediate decode and target addition into the IF next-PC\\ncone and lost too much Fmax. CoreMark still has hot loop branches and direct\\njumps, so the promising predictor direction is to avoid recomputing targets\\nin IF and instead reuse targets already resolved in EX.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The previous static backward-branch predictor recovered some taken-branch\\ncycles, but it put immediate decode and target addition into the IF next-PC\\ncone and lost too much Fmax. CoreMark still has hot loop branches and direct\\njumps, so the promising predictor direction is to avoid recomputing targets\\nin IF and instead reuse targets already resolved in EX.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a small direct-mapped branch target buffer with 2-bit taken counters,\\ntrained when branches and jumps resolve in EX. IF predicts taken only on a\\nvalid tag hit whose counter is taken, then uses the stored target directly;\\nmisses fall through to pc+4. Carry the predicted next PC through ID/EX so EX\\nredirects only when the resolved architectural next PC differs from the\\nprediction. This should turn steady-state CoreMark loop-back branches into\\ncorrect-path fetches while keeping the IF critical path to a tag compare,\\ncounter bit, target mux, and the existing pc+4 adder rather than the failed\\nimmediate-decode plus target-adder cone.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicted-next-PC and prediction-valid fields to IF/ID and ID/EX pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a small EX-trained direct-mapped BTB/BHT and select stored targets on valid taken hits, with fall-through as the default.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Propagate IF prediction...\n  Line 9: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r3s1\", \"title\": \"MEM-to-EX load-use bypass\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage pipeline always inserts a bubble when an instruction\\nconsumes the destination of the immediately preceding load. That is safe but\\npessimistic for the zero-wait or ready dmem cycles that dominate the FPGA and\\nrandom-stall CoreMark runs: the load value is already formed in MEM while the\\ndependent instruction would be in EX. Previous frontend structural work lost\\ntoo much Fmax, so the better IPC target is a local backend bypass that leaves\\nIF next-PC timing untouched.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage pipeline always inserts a bubble when an instruction\\nconsumes the destination of the immediately preceding load. That is safe but\\npessimistic for the zero-wait or ready dmem cycles that dominate the FPGA and\\nrandom-stall CoreMark runs: the load value is already formed in MEM while the\\ndependent instruction would be in EX. Previous frontend structural work lost\\ntoo much Fmax, so the better IPC target is a local backend bypass that leaves\\nIF next-PC timing untouched.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a MEM-stage load-data bypass into the EX operand forwarding network and\\nchange load-use hazard handling so the dependent instruction stalls only when\\nthe load is actually waiting on dmem or cannot produce a valid value. The MEM\\nstage should expose the sign/zero-extended load result plus a valid rd tag;\\nEX should select that value ahead of the older MEM/WB path for matching rs1 or\\nrs2 operands. This should remove common one-cycle load-use bubbles in\\nCoreMark while preserving the existing single-retire RVFI contract and keeping\\nbranch prediction/front-end timing unchanged.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire a MEM-stage load bypass value/tag/valid path from mem_stage into the EX forwarding network while preserving the nret=1 ...\n  Line 10: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r3s2\", \"title\": \"Single-entry loop target predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts recovered some control-flow cycles but lost fitness by\\nputting too much work in the fetch next-PC path: immediate target calculation\\nfor static prediction, then tag/counter/target array lookup for a tiny BTB.\\nCoreMark is still loop-heavy, so the best remaining predictor angle is a much\\nnarrower loop-back predictor that only remembers one resolved backward branch\\ntarget and avoids any IF instruction decode or target addition.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts recovered some control-flow cycles but lost fitness by\\nputting too much work in the fetch next-PC path: immediate target calculation\\nfor static prediction, then tag/counter/target array lookup for a tiny BTB.\\nCoreMark is still loop-heavy, so the best remaining predictor angle is a much\\nnarrower loop-back predictor that only remembers one resolved backward branch\\ntarget and avoids any IF instruction decode or target addition.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a single-entry EX-trained backward-loop target latch. When EX resolves a\\ntaken conditional branch whose target is below its PC, record {branch_pc,\\nbranch_target}; when IF later fetches the same PC, predict the stored target.\\nClear or mark not-taken when that same branch resolves fall-through so loop\\nexits recover after one mispredict. Carry predicted-next-PC metadata through\\nID/EX so EX suppresses redirects on correct predictions and redirects only on\\nmismatches. This should save repeated inner-loop taken-branch bubbles with far\\nless fetch-side cost than the failed static predictor or BTB.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicted-next-PC metadata to IF/ID and ID/EX bundles for one-entry loop prediction verification in EX.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a single-entry ba...\n  Line 11: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r4s0\", \"title\": \"Case-based MEM byte lanes\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core has already moved rare high-half multiply and divide\\nwork out of the common EX path, so the next safest micro-optimization is a\\nhot load/store datapath cleanup rather than another predictor or bypass.\\nCoreMark performs many byte, halfword, and word memory accesses, and the MEM\\nstage currently builds masks with variable shifts and extracts load data with\\na variable word shift before sign extension. Even if synthesis simplifies\\nsome of this, the generic shifter/mask form can add LUT depth and routing on\\na path that every load reaches.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core has already moved rare high-half multiply and divide\\nwork out of the common EX path, so the next safest micro-optimization is a\\nhot load/store datapath cleanup rather than another predictor or bypass.\\nCoreMark performs many byte, halfword, and word memory accesses, and the MEM\\nstage currently builds masks with variable shifts and extracts load data with\\na variable word shift before sign extension. Even if synthesis simplifies\\nsome of this, the generic shifter/mask form can add LUT depth and routing on\\na path that every load reaches.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Rewrite the MEM-stage byte-lane logic as explicit case statements keyed by\\naddress bits and access width. Generate store masks, replicated write data,\\nload byte/halfword selection, and RVFI masks directly per lane instead of\\nusing `<<` and `>> (addr[1:0] * 8)` expressions. This preserves the existing\\none-cycle MEM latency, dmem handshake behavior, misalignment trapping, and\\nnret=1 RVFI contract while giving yosys/nextpnr a smaller mux network for the\\nload-data and mask paths. The expected gain is mostly Fmax with no intentional\\nCoreMark cycle-count change.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"R...\n  Line 12: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"Register forwarding selects\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"Recent structural IPC attempts added frontend/backend muxing and lost more Fmax than they recovered in cycles. The remaining attractive structural target is the EX operand path itself: live rd/rs compare and priority-select logic currently feeds the ALU and low-half MUL muxes every cycle. Retiming those decisions into the ID/EX register should shorten the hot EX cone without changing branch prediction, load-use behavior, or the nret=1 RVFI contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent structural IPC attempts added frontend/backend muxing and lost more Fmax than they recovered in cycles. The remaining attractive structural target is the EX operand path itself: live rd/rs compare and priority-select logic currently feeds the ALU and low-half MUL muxes every cycle. Retiming those decisions into the ID/EX register should shorten the hot EX cone without changing branch prediction, load-use behavior, or the nret=1 RVFI contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Compute the forwarding source for the instruction while it is still in decode, then carry two registered forwarding-select fields in id_ex_t. Decode can compare the IF/ID rs addresses against the current ID/EX producer, which will be EX/MEM next cycle, and the current EX/MEM producer, which will be MEM/WB next cycle. The existing load-use bubble remains in place, so a load immediately ahead is not treated as an EX/MEM-forwardable producer. EX then uses only the registered select bits plus the existing forwarded data buses, removing the live comparator/priority network from the ALU and one-cycle MUL timing path while preserving identical IPC and stall semantics.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add rs1/rs2 forwarding-select fields to the ID/EX pipeline bundle so forwarding decisions are registered with the instruction.\"...\n  Line 13: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r4s2\", \"title\": \"Tiny RAS return predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Prior branch predictors regressed because they put target adders, tag compares,\\nor predicted-PC metadata on already-sensitive frontend and EX paths. CoreMark\\nstill executes call/return control flow around its benchmark kernels, and\\nreturns are predictable with much less IF logic than conditional branches or a\\nBTB: an exact `ret` instruction compare plus a registered return-stack top.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior branch predictors regressed because they put target adders, tag compares,\\nor predicted-PC metadata on already-sensitive frontend and EX paths. CoreMark\\nstill executes call/return control flow around its benchmark kernels, and\\nreturns are predictable with much less IF logic than conditional branches or a\\nBTB: an exact `ret` instruction compare plus a registered return-stack top.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a tiny return-address-stack predictor for canonical RISC-V returns only.\\nTrain the stack when EX resolves link-register JAL/JALR calls, and when IF\\nfetches `jalr x0, 0(x1)` or `jalr x0, 0(x5)` with a valid stack entry, use the\\nstored top as the next PC. Carry only return-prediction metadata to EX so a\\ncorrectly predicted return suppresses the normal JALR redirect, while a bad or\\nempty-stack prediction redirects to the architecturally resolved target. This\\nshould recover return redirect bubbles with far less timing cost than the\\nfailed static branch, BTB, and loop-target predictors because IF does not\\ncompute branch immediates, add targets, or compare fetch PCs against tags.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add compact return-prediction metadata to IF/ID and ID/EX bundles for EX redirect suppression and recovery.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a tiny registered return-address stack, exact canonical-ret detection, and ...\n  Line 14: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r5s0\", \"title\": \"Source-aware load-use stalls\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current hazard unit treats both raw rs1 and rs2 bitfields as live source\\noperands for every instruction. That is conservative, but it can insert a\\none-cycle load-use bubble when the following instruction is LUI, AUIPC, JAL,\\nEBREAK/FENCE, or an I-type instruction whose immediate bits merely alias the\\nprevious load destination. CoreMark contains many load/immediate/control-flow\\nsequences, so avoiding these false bubbles should improve cycles without\\nadding a bypass path or fetch-side predictor logic.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current hazard unit treats both raw rs1 and rs2 bitfields as live source\\noperands for every instruction. That is conservative, but it can insert a\\none-cycle load-use bubble when the following instruction is LUI, AUIPC, JAL,\\nEBREAK/FENCE, or an I-type instruction whose immediate bits merely alias the\\nprevious load destination. CoreMark contains many load/immediate/control-flow\\nsequences, so avoiding these false bubbles should improve cycles without\\nadding a bypass path or fetch-side predictor logic.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add small source-usage qualification for load-use detection and decode-time\\nforwarding select generation. The hazard unit should only compare a pending\\nload destination against rs1 when the IF/ID instruction architecturally reads\\nrs1, and only against rs2 when it architecturally reads rs2. Keep true\\nload-use bubbles for OP, BRANCH, STORE, LOAD/OP-IMM/JALR rs1 dependencies,\\npreserve the existing no-MEM-bypass policy, and leave RVFI retirement and\\ntrap behavior unchanged. This is a localized IPC micro-optimization with far\\nless timing risk than the failed MEM-to-EX load bypass.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Qualify load-use hazard comparisons with compact IF/ID source-use decoding so unused...\n  Line 16: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r5s2\", \"title\": \"Decode-stage JAL target predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts lost fitness because they put branch immediate decode,\\ntag compares, target arrays, or RAS logic directly in the fetch next-PC path.\\nCoreMark still contains direct calls and unconditional jumps, and those are\\ndeterministic once the instruction is visible in decode. A narrower predictor\\ncan recover some redirect bubbles without adding conditional branch direction\\nstate or a BTB-style lookup to every fetch.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts lost fitness because they put branch immediate decode,\\ntag compares, target arrays, or RAS logic directly in the fetch next-PC path.\\nCoreMark still contains direct calls and unconditional jumps, and those are\\ndeterministic once the instruction is visible in decode. A narrower predictor\\ncan recover some redirect bubbles without adding conditional branch direction\\nstate or a BTB-style lookup to every fetch.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an early direct-JAL target predictor in decode: when ID sees an aligned\\nJAL instruction, compute pc+J_imm using the existing decoded immediate path\\nand redirect IF one stage earlier than the normal EX redirect. Carry a compact\\npredicted-direct-jump bit and predicted target through ID/EX so EX suppresses\\nthe ordinary JAL redirect when the prediction matches, and recovers normally\\nfor misaligned targets or any mismatch. This focuses the predictor on\\nunconditional direct control flow, avoiding the failed conditional-branch,\\nloop-BTB, and RAS structures while still saving bubbles on CoreMark calls and\\ndirect jumps.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add compact direct-JAL prediction metadata to IF/ID or ID/EX pipeline bundles for EX redirect suppression and recovery.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect aligned JAL instruct...\n  Line 17: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r6s0\", \"title\": \"Precompute PC-relative EX values\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best results indicate that fitness gains are coming from Fmax,\\nnot from added prediction or bypass IPC. The EX stage still recomputes\\npc+4 and pc+imm for branch, JAL, JALR link, and AUIPC handling, and it keeps\\nan is_auipc mux in front of the fast ALU operand path. Those deterministic\\nPC-relative values can be registered before EX instead of sitting in the\\nALU/MUL and redirect timing cones.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best results indicate that fitness gains are coming from Fmax,\\nnot from added prediction or bypass IPC. The EX stage still recomputes\\npc+4 and pc+imm for branch, JAL, JALR link, and AUIPC handling, and it keeps\\nan is_auipc mux in front of the fast ALU operand path. Those deterministic\\nPC-relative values can be registered before EX instead of sitting in the\\nALU/MUL and redirect timing cones.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add registered pc_plus4 and pc_imm fields to the ID/EX payload, computed in\\nid_stage from the existing immediate generator output. Use those registered\\nvalues in ex_stage for direct branch and JAL targets, AUIPC rd_wdata,\\nJAL/JALR link writeback, and fall-through pc_next. JALR target calculation\\nremains in EX because it depends on the forwarded rs1 operand. This should\\nremove PC adders and the AUIPC operand mux from hot EX paths without changing\\npipeline depth, stall policy, RVFI ordering, or CoreMark cycle count.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add registered pc_plus4 and pc_imm fields to id_ex_t so PC-relative values are available in EX without recomputation.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute pc_plus4 and pc_imm while latching ID/EX, using the existing immediate generator output and preserving flush/stall behavior.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Use the ...\n  Line 18: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r6s1\", \"title\": \"Slim unused pipeline sidebands\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"Recent structural wins came from shortening hot pipeline cones without adding\\nnew IPC machinery, while fetch buffers, load bypasses, and predictors lost\\nmore Fmax than they recovered. The current RTL still carries some metadata\\nthat is not consumed after EX, including EX/MEM branch_taken and\\nbranch_target fields plus an is_lui control bit that is redundant with\\nALU_LUI. Those dead sidebands add registers, mux fanout, and routing pressure\\non a design where small retiming changes have already moved fitness.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent structural wins came from shortening hot pipeline cones without adding\\nnew IPC machinery, while fetch buffers, load bypasses, and predictors lost\\nmore Fmax than they recovered. The current RTL still carries some metadata\\nthat is not consumed after EX, including EX/MEM branch_taken and\\nbranch_target fields plus an is_lui control bit that is redundant with\\nALU_LUI. Those dead sidebands add registers, mux fanout, and routing pressure\\non a design where small retiming changes have already moved fitness.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Prune the unused pipeline sidebands rather than changing execution behavior:\\nremove branch_taken and branch_target from ex_mem_t and stop registering them,\\nand remove the dead is_lui control bit from ctrl_t while keeping LUI legality\\nrepresented by ALU_LUI and the existing immediate path. Branch redirect and\\npc_next calculation still use local EX signals in the same cycle, so IPC,\\nstall behavior, traps, and the nret=1 RVFI contract are unchanged. The smaller\\npipeline payload should reduce EX/MEM fanout, backend register count, and\\nnextpnr routing pressure, yielding a modest Fmax-driven fitness gain.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the unused is_lui control bit and dead EX/MEM b...\n  Line 19: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r6s2\", \"title\": \"Countdown loop predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts recovered possible control-flow cycles but lost more\\nFPGA fitness through fetch-side instruction decode, target adders, BTB/RAS\\nlookup, or exact PC compare paths. CoreMark is still loop-heavy, so the most\\npromising remaining predictor angle is to keep loop prediction state cheap\\nenough that it does not dominate the IF next-PC cone.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts recovered possible control-flow cycles but lost more\\nFPGA fitness through fetch-side instruction decode, target adders, BTB/RAS\\nlookup, or exact PC compare paths. CoreMark is still loop-heavy, so the most\\npromising remaining predictor angle is to keep loop prediction state cheap\\nenough that it does not dominate the IF next-PC cone.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a single-entry backward-loop countdown predictor trained by EX when a\\nconditional branch resolves taken to a lower PC. Store the loop target and\\nthe branch-to-target distance in words, then count sequential fetch advances\\nfrom the target; when the counter reaches zero, predict the stored loop\\ntarget without decoding the fetched instruction or comparing the fetch PC\\nagainst a tag. Carry compact prediction metadata through ID/EX so EX can\\nsuppress the normal taken-branch redirect on a correct loop prediction and\\nrecover to pc+4 on the loop exit or any mismatch. This should preserve most\\nof the useful inner-loop benefit of the failed loop/BTB predictors while\\nreplacing the IF exact-PC/tag compare with a small zero-count check.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add compact predicted-loop-taken and predicted-target metadata to IF/ID and ID/EX bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add the single-entry backward-loop countdown predictor, update it on resolved branch training, and se...\n  Line 20: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r7s0\", \"title\": \"Share branch compare flags\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Recent successful bench-core changes improved fitness by shortening hot FPGA\\ntiming paths without adding new prediction, buffering, or bypass machinery.\\nThe EX stage still builds branch decisions with separate equality, signed,\\nand unsigned comparisons selected by branch_op. CoreMark is branch-heavy, and\\na taken branch redirect path must resolve in the same cycle as the ALU path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent successful bench-core changes improved fitness by shortening hot FPGA\\ntiming paths without adding new prediction, buffering, or bypass machinery.\\nThe EX stage still builds branch decisions with separate equality, signed,\\nand unsigned comparisons selected by branch_op. CoreMark is branch-heavy, and\\na taken branch redirect path must resolve in the same cycle as the ALU path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the per-branch comparison expressions in rtl/ex_stage.sv with shared\\ncompare flags: one equality check, one unsigned less-than flag, and a small\\nsign-bit correction for signed less-than. BEQ/BNE and BGE/BGEU can use these\\nflags and inversions instead of independent signed/unsigned comparator cones.\\nThis keeps the five-stage pipeline, redirect timing, load-use policy, RVFI\\nordering, and CoreMark cycle count unchanged while giving synthesis a smaller\\nEX branch-condition mux network and potentially improving Fmax.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute shared branch comparison flags and use them for all BRANCH funct3 cases, preserving existing redirect and misalignment semantics.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute shared branch comparison flags and use them for all BRANCH funct3 cases, preserving existing redirect and misalignment semanti...\n  Line 21: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r7s1\", \"title\": \"LUTRAM-backed unreset regfile\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"Recent structural attempts that added frontend prediction, fetch buffering,\\nMEM bypassing, or extra WB state regressed because they added muxing and\\ncontrol to already sensitive paths. The current register file is still a\\n32x32 reset-cleared, two-read flop array with write-first bypass muxes; that\\nreset loop and wide read muxing consume many FFs and routing resources even\\nthough RV32I only requires x0 to be zero after reset. Removing the\\nnon-architectural full-register reset is a localized structural change with\\nno intended CoreMark cycle-count impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent structural attempts that added frontend prediction, fetch buffering,\\nMEM bypassing, or extra WB state regressed because they added muxing and\\ncontrol to already sensitive paths. The current register file is still a\\n32x32 reset-cleared, two-read flop array with write-first bypass muxes; that\\nreset loop and wide read muxing consume many FFs and routing resources even\\nthough RV32I only requires x0 to be zero after reset. Removing the\\nnon-architectural full-register reset is a localized structural change with\\nno intended CoreMark cycle-count impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Recode rtl/reg_file.sv as an unreset, duplicated two-read-bank register file\\nsuitable for distributed LUT RAM inference. Keep both banks written together,\\nkeep x0 hardwired to zero, and retain the explicit same-cycle write-first\\nbypass so the existing decode/forwarding contract is unchanged. With reset\\nremoved from the 31 writable registers, yosys/nextpnr should have less reset\\nfanout, fewer flop-based read muxes, and better packing/routing around the\\ndecode-to-ID/EX path, improving Fmax without changing IPC, RVFI ordering, or\\nany hard invariant.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/reg_file.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the...\n  Line 22: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r7s2\", \"title\": \"Registered lookahead loop predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"CoreMark is still loop-heavy, so the remaining control-flow opportunity is\\nreducing repeated taken backward-branch redirects. The prior predictor\\nattempts show that the useful predictor must not put instruction decode,\\ntarget adders, BTB tag compares, or RAS reads on the same-cycle IF next-PC\\npath, because Fmax loss dominates the saved bubbles.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"CoreMark is still loop-heavy, so the remaining control-flow opportunity is\\nreducing repeated taken backward-branch redirects. The prior predictor\\nattempts show that the useful predictor must not put instruction decode,\\ntarget adders, BTB tag compares, or RAS reads on the same-cycle IF next-PC\\npath, because Fmax loss dominates the saved bubbles.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a tiny EX-trained backward-loop predictor whose lookup is performed one\\nfetch ahead for the next sequential PC and latched before it can affect the\\nPC update. While fetching PC P, IF compares the trained loop branch PC\\nagainst P+4 and captures a registered hit/target for the instruction that\\nwill be fetched next; when that next instruction is actually at the\\nloop-branch PC, the PC update selects the already-registered target with no\\nlive tag compare or target-array read in the PC feedback cone. EX trains the\\nentry on taken backward conditional branches and invalidates it when the same\\nbranch resolves not taken, while carried prediction metadata lets EX suppress\\ncorrect predicted redirects or recover normally on loop exit. This keeps the\\npredictor focused on hot loop-back branches and directly addresses the timing\\nfailure mode of the earlier static, BTB, RAS, and countdown predictors.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add compact predicted-taken and predicted-target fields to IF/ID and ID/EX bundles so E...\n  Line 23: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r8s0\", \"title\": \"Narrow slow MULH adder\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The best prior micro-optimizations improved fitness by shortening FPGA timing\\ncones without adding frontend prediction or load bypass control. The slow\\nRV32M unit is still synthesized into the design, and its high-half multiply\\nloop currently uses a 64-bit accumulator plus a shifted 64-bit multiplicand,\\ncreating a wide carry path for operations that CoreMark rarely executes.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The best prior micro-optimizations improved fitness by shortening FPGA timing\\ncones without adding frontend prediction or load bypass control. The slow\\nRV32M unit is still synthesized into the design, and its high-half multiply\\nloop currently uses a 64-bit accumulator plus a shifted 64-bit multiplicand,\\ncreating a wide carry path for operations that CoreMark rarely executes.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the slow MULH/MULHU/MULHSU iterative multiply datapath in m_unit.sv\\nwith a right-shift partial-product algorithm that adds the 32-bit magnitude\\noperand into the upper half of a combined product register. This keeps the\\nexisting multi-cycle behavior and separate finish-state sign correction, but\\nreduces the per-cycle multiply carry path from roughly 64 bits to about 33\\nbits. CoreMark should see nearly unchanged cycle count because low-half MUL\\nremains single-cycle in the fast ALU and slow high-half multiplies are rare,\\nwhile median FPGA Fmax may improve from the narrower m_unit timing cone.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/m_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Rewrite the real slow high-half multiply loop to use a combined right-shift product register and a narrower upper-half add, preserving ALTOPS behavior, result_ready holding, and existing DIV/REM logic.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Keep or add focused MULH, MULHU, and MULHSU edge vectors that cover sign correction, hi...\n  Line 24: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r8s1\", \"title\": \"Registered low-half MUL path\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"Prior structural wins came from taking rare RV32M work out of the common EX\\nresult cone, while frontend predictors, fetch buffering, MEM bypassing, and\\nregfile rewrites all lost more timing than they recovered. The remaining\\nhigh-cost logic still present on every fast EX timing analysis path is the\\nsingle-cycle 32x32 low-half MUL in alu.sv. CoreMark needs MUL support, but it\\ndoes not execute MUL every cycle, so a small MUL-only latency penalty may be\\ncheaper than keeping the multiplier in the ADD/load-address/branch ALU cone.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior structural wins came from taking rare RV32M work out of the common EX\\nresult cone, while frontend predictors, fetch buffering, MEM bypassing, and\\nregfile rewrites all lost more timing than they recovered. The remaining\\nhigh-cost logic still present on every fast EX timing analysis path is the\\nsingle-cycle 32x32 low-half MUL in alu.sv. CoreMark needs MUL support, but it\\ndoes not execute MUL every cycle, so a small MUL-only latency penalty may be\\ncheaper than keeping the multiplier in the ADD/load-address/branch ALU cone.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Split ALU_MUL out of the combinational fast ALU and handle it with a tiny\\nregistered low-half multiply side path in EX. Non-MUL RV32I ALU operations,\\nbranch compares, load/store address generation, JAL/JALR link values, and the\\nexisting slow high-half/DIV/REM m_unit behavior should remain unchanged. When\\nALU_MUL reaches EX, the pipeline holds for the registered product, then emits\\nexactly one EX/MEM result with the original RVFI operands and order. Under\\nRISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS the side path should register the same formal substitute\\nexpression instead of the real product. This should remove the DSP/multiplier\\npath from the common ALU output mux and improve Tang Nano Fmax enough to\\noffset occasional MUL bubbles in CoreMark.\\n\", \"expected_impa...\n  Line 25: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r8s2\", \"title\": \"JAL-only target cache\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts show that CoreMark does not repay broad IF-stage\\nbranch machinery: static backward prediction, BTBs, loop predictors, and RAS\\nvariants all lost Fmax through target adders, tag/counter lookup, recovery\\nmetadata, or extra next-PC muxing. The remaining control-flow predictor angle\\nwith a plausible timing budget is to predict only direct JAL instructions,\\nwhich are unconditionally taken and do not need direction counters or branch\\ncondition state.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts show that CoreMark does not repay broad IF-stage\\nbranch machinery: static backward prediction, BTBs, loop predictors, and RAS\\nvariants all lost Fmax through target adders, tag/counter lookup, recovery\\nmetadata, or extra next-PC muxing. The remaining control-flow predictor angle\\nwith a plausible timing budget is to predict only direct JAL instructions,\\nwhich are unconditionally taken and do not need direction counters or branch\\ncondition state.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a tiny EX-trained target cache for aligned direct JAL/JAL-x0 instructions\\nonly. When EX resolves an aligned direct JAL, store its PC signature and\\nresolved target in a two-entry cache; when IF fetches a JAL opcode with a\\nmatching signature, use the stored target and carry compact predicted-JAL\\nmetadata to EX. EX suppresses the normal redirect when the stored target\\nmatches the resolved JAL target, and otherwise falls back to the existing\\nredirect/trap path. This avoids the failed static predictor's IF immediate\\ndecode and target adder, avoids BTB direction counters, avoids conditional\\nbranch prediction entirely, and targets only always-taken call/jump bubbles\\nthat can be recovered with minimal predictor state.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 1, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add compact predicted-JA...\n  Line 26: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r9s0\", \"title\": \"Isolate fast EX result mux\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best result came from registering low-half MUL so the 32x32\\nmultiplier no longer sits in the common ALU cone. However, normal ADD,\\nload-address, branch-adjacent, and jump-link results still feed the EX/MEM\\nregister through a shared result select that includes low-half MUL and the\\nslow M-unit result. CoreMark executes M operations sparsely, so keeping\\nthose M-result inputs on the every-cycle fast EX register input may cost\\nFmax without improving IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best result came from registering low-half MUL so the 32x32\\nmultiplier no longer sits in the common ALU cone. However, normal ADD,\\nload-address, branch-adjacent, and jump-link results still feed the EX/MEM\\nregister through a shared result select that includes low-half MUL and the\\nslow M-unit result. CoreMark executes M operations sparsely, so keeping\\nthose M-result inputs on the every-cycle fast EX register input may cost\\nFmax without improving IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Rewrite the EX-stage commit result selection so ordinary single-cycle\\ninstructions drive EX/MEM from a fast result path containing only the ALU\\nresult or JAL/JALR link value, while low-half MUL and slow M results are\\nselected only in the result-valid commit branch. This preserves the existing\\nregistered MUL latency, slow-M handshake, stall behavior, RVFI operands, and\\nnret=1 retirement contract, but should remove a 32-bit M-result mux level\\nfrom the hot non-M EX path and modestly improve Tang Nano Fmax.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Separate the fast ALU/jump-link EX/MEM result path from MUL and slow M result-valid commit paths, preserving existing M handshakes and RVFI operand latching.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"fi...\n  Line 28: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r9s2\", \"title\": \"Stall-shadow branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts on this core lost fitness because they put target\\nadders, tag compares, counters, return-stack reads, or prediction recovery\\nmuxes on the normal IF next-PC path. The random-stall CoreMark methodology\\nstill creates cycles where IF is holding a valid instruction while decode,\\ndmem, or a slow M operation is stalled. Those otherwise idle hold cycles can\\nbe used to prepare a prediction without making every fetch pay the full\\npredictor timing cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts on this core lost fitness because they put target\\nadders, tag compares, counters, return-stack reads, or prediction recovery\\nmuxes on the normal IF next-PC path. The random-stall CoreMark methodology\\nstill creates cycles where IF is holding a valid instruction while decode,\\ndmem, or a slow M operation is stalled. Those otherwise idle hold cycles can\\nbe used to prepare a prediction without making every fetch pay the full\\npredictor timing cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an opportunistic stall-shadow predictor that only arms while IF is\\nstalled on a valid held instruction. During the hold window, predecode only\\naligned direct JALs and negative-immediate conditional branches, compute the\\nstatic taken target, and store that target in a small registered shadow slot.\\nWhen the stall releases for the same held PC/instruction, IF selects the\\nalready-registered target and carries compact predicted-next-PC metadata to\\nEX. EX suppresses the normal redirect when the resolved next PC matches the\\nshadow prediction and recovers through the existing flush path on mismatch or\\nloop exit. This targets control-flow bubbles that immediately follow existing\\nload-use, dmem, imem, or slow-M stalls while avoiding live predictor lookup,\\nimmediate decode, and target addition on ordinary fall-through fetch cycles.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitne...\n  Line 29: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r10s0\", \"title\": \"Control-only datapath resets\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Recent bench wins have come from small Fmax-oriented cleanups that avoid new\\nprediction, bypass, or frontend machinery. The current RTL still resets large\\ndatapath payloads in ID/EX, EX/MEM, MEM/WB, and the RV32M side units even\\nthough only valid/control bits are required to suppress retirement, writes,\\nredirects, and memory side effects after reset or flush.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent bench wins have come from small Fmax-oriented cleanups that avoid new\\nprediction, bypass, or frontend machinery. The current RTL still resets large\\ndatapath payloads in ID/EX, EX/MEM, MEM/WB, and the RV32M side units even\\nthough only valid/control bits are required to suppress retirement, writes,\\nredirects, and memory side effects after reset or flush.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Convert pipeline and M-unit reset handling to reset only valid, state, and\\nside-effecting control fields while leaving operand/result/PC/data payload\\nflops unreset when their associated valid/control bits are clear. Flushes and\\nreset bubbles must still clear ctrl.mem_read, ctrl.mem_write, ctrl.reg_write,\\nctrl.is_branch, ctrl.is_jump, and valid so invalid instructions cannot retire,\\nredirect, or touch memory. This should reduce synchronous-reset muxing and\\nglobal reset fanout across hundreds of FPGA flops without changing pipeline\\ndepth, CoreMark cycle count, RVFI order, or trap behavior.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Change ID/EX reset and flush bubbles to clear valid and control fields only, leaving data payload flops unreset when invalid.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Change EX/MEM reset bubbles and slow-M emitted bubbles to clear valid/control side-effect fields only while keeping operand/result payload flops off the reset network.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv...\n  Line 30: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r10s1\", \"title\": \"Posted store buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current pipeline freezes all stages whenever a store reaches MEM while\\nio_dmemReady is low, even though the store has no register result and many\\nfollowing CoreMark instructions are independent integer work. Prior\\nstructural attempts that added frontend prediction or load-use bypassing\\npaid too much timing cost, but store-side decoupling can target dStall IPC\\nloss with only local MEM/hazard changes and no IF next-PC cone growth.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current pipeline freezes all stages whenever a store reaches MEM while\\nio_dmemReady is low, even though the store has no register result and many\\nfollowing CoreMark instructions are independent integer work. Prior\\nstructural attempts that added frontend prediction or load-use bypassing\\npaid too much timing cost, but store-side decoupling can target dStall IPC\\nloss with only local MEM/hazard changes and no IF next-PC cone growth.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a single-entry posted store buffer at the MEM stage. When a store is in\\nEX/MEM and dmem is not ready, capture its address, replicated write data,\\nmask, and RVFI memory fields, allow the store to retire once into MEM/WB,\\nand let younger non-memory instructions continue while the buffer drains to\\nthe external dmem port. Stall subsequent loads or stores until the buffered\\nstore has been accepted, preserving in-order memory semantics without a\\nload-forwarding network. This should hide a meaningful fraction of random\\nstore dStall cycles in CoreMark while keeping the nret=1 RVFI retirement\\ncontract unchanged and avoiding the frontend timing penalties that hurt\\nearlier predictor/buffer experiments.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add minimal store-buffer metadata fields or helper typedefs if needed, without changing the nret=1 RVFI port contr...\n  Line 31: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r10s2\", \"title\": \"Exact trivial-MUL result predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Prior CoreMark branch predictors repeatedly lost fitness by adding lookup,\\ntarget, mux, and recovery logic to the IF next-PC path. The current best\\ncore instead gained by registering low-half MUL, but that makes every MUL\\npay an EX hold even when the result is an obvious function of a zero, one,\\nor minus-one operand. A predictor that classifies only those exact operand\\ncases can recover some MUL bubbles without touching fetch prediction.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior CoreMark branch predictors repeatedly lost fitness by adding lookup,\\ntarget, mux, and recovery logic to the IF next-PC path. The current best\\ncore instead gained by registering low-half MUL, but that makes every MUL\\npay an EX hold even when the result is an obvious function of a zero, one,\\nor minus-one operand. A predictor that classifies only those exact operand\\ncases can recover some MUL bubbles without touching fetch prediction.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an exact operand-class result predictor for ALU_MUL inside EX. When a\\nvalid low-half MUL has an operand of 0, 1, or 0xffffffff, bypass the\\nregistered multiplier and emit the known result in the normal EX/MEM commit\\ncycle; all other MULs continue using the existing mul_unit hold protocol.\\nThis keeps branch prediction out of the sensitive frontend, preserves exact\\nRV32M semantics with no speculative rollback, and may improve CoreMark\\ncycles if its matrix/state kernels contain trivial multiplier operands while\\nkeeping the common non-MUL ALU path nearly unchanged.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 1, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add exact zero/one/minus-one ALU_MUL result classification, suppress mul_unit start/EX hold on hits, and preserve existing slow-M and RVFI operand latching behavior.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_mul_fastpath.py\", \"description\": \"Add co...\n  Line 32: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r11s0\", \"title\": \"Share EX PC adders\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The best bench-core results have come from small Fmax-oriented changes that\\nkeep the pipeline shape unchanged and avoid new prediction, bypass, or\\nexception fast paths. The current EX stage still recomputes pc+imm for both\\nbranch/JAL target handling and AUIPC, recomputes pc+4 for link and fall-through\\npaths, and places a rare AUIPC-controlled 32-bit mux in front of the fast ALU\\noperand path used by ordinary ADD, load/store address generation, and branch\\nwork. The prior PC-precompute attempt regressed because it added ID-side\\nadders and wider ID/EX state; this narrower cleanup keeps the adders local to\\nEX and only removes duplicated source expressions and a hot input mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The best bench-core results have come from small Fmax-oriented changes that\\nkeep the pipeline shape unchanged and avoid new prediction, bypass, or\\nexception fast paths. The current EX stage still recomputes pc+imm for both\\nbranch/JAL target handling and AUIPC, recomputes pc+4 for link and fall-through\\npaths, and places a rare AUIPC-controlled 32-bit mux in front of the fast ALU\\noperand path used by ordinary ADD, load/store address generation, and branch\\nwork. The prior PC-precompute attempt regressed because it added ID-side\\nadders and wider ID/EX state; this narrower cleanup keeps the adders local to\\nEX and only removes duplicated source expressions and a hot input mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"In rtl/ex_stage.sv, create local shared pc_plus4 and pc_imm_sum wires and use\\nthem for branch targets, JAL targets, AUIPC rd_wdata, JAL/JALR link data, and\\npc_next fall-through. At the same time, remove the is_auipc selection from the\\nALU input mux so normal ALU and load/store address operations feed rs1 directly\\ninto the ALU; AUIPC should select the shared pc_imm_sum only at the EX/MEM\\nresult boundary. This should shorten the common EX operand-to-ALU cone w...\n  Line 33: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r11s1\", \"title\": \"Split WB forwarding shadow\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"Prior structural wins came from removing hot-path logic without adding new\\nfrontend prediction or memory-order machinery. The current MEM/WB register\\nretains every RVFI and datapath field during a dmem stall solely so a held\\ndependent instruction can keep seeing the previous WB forwarding value. That\\nmakes hold_mem_wb fan out across a wide retirement bundle even though only\\nthe WB forwarding data must survive the stall.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior structural wins came from removing hot-path logic without adding new\\nfrontend prediction or memory-order machinery. The current MEM/WB register\\nretains every RVFI and datapath field during a dmem stall solely so a held\\ndependent instruction can keep seeing the previous WB forwarding value. That\\nmakes hold_mem_wb fan out across a wide retirement bundle even though only\\nthe WB forwarding data must survive the stall.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the wide MEM/WB hold behavior with a narrow forwarding shadow for the\\nWB value used by EX-stage MEM/WB forwarding. During dmem stalls, MEM/WB can\\ncontinue capturing a valid-cleared bubble from the held EX/MEM load/store,\\nwhile a small shadow register preserves the previous wb_w_data for any held\\ndependent instruction whose ID/EX forwarding select is FWD_MEM_WB. This keeps\\nRVFI retirement precise, avoids double writes, preserves the existing load-use\\nand dmem-stall semantics, and should reduce high-fanout hold routing around\\nthe wide MEM/WB/RVFI bundle for a modest Fmax-driven gain.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a narrow WB-forwarding shadow register and feed EX with the shadowed value only while MEM/WB is valid-cleared for a dmem stall.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Change dmem-stall handling so MEM/WB no longer retains all data fie...\n  Line 34: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r11s2\", \"title\": \"Redirect target replay cache\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Every prior control-flow predictor on this core lost fitness because it put\\nlookup, target-add, next-PC muxing, or prediction metadata on the normal\\nfetch path. The existing pipeline still pays a redirect bubble for hot loop\\nbranches and direct jumps after EX has already resolved the correct target.\\nA predictor that only acts on resolved redirects can target those bubbles\\nwithout perturbing the common fall-through `pc + 4` fetch path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Every prior control-flow predictor on this core lost fitness because it put\\nlookup, target-add, next-PC muxing, or prediction metadata on the normal\\nfetch path. The existing pipeline still pays a redirect bubble for hot loop\\nbranches and direct jumps after EX has already resolved the correct target.\\nA predictor that only acts on resolved redirects can target those bubbles\\nwithout perturbing the common fall-through `pc + 4` fetch path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a tiny target-instruction replay cache in IF, filled by ordinary\\nsuccessful instruction fetches as `{pc, instr, pc_plus4}` entries. When EX\\nasserts a redirect to a cached target, IF injects the cached target\\ninstruction into ID in that same cycle and advances the PC to the cached\\n`pc_plus4`, while the hazard unit suppresses only the redirect flush that\\nwould have killed this injected instruction. Cache misses keep the existing\\nredirect behavior exactly. This is a predictor of the target instruction,\\nnot a branch-direction predictor: there is no EX redirect suppression, no\\nspeculative wrong-path retirement, and no predictor lookup on normal\\nfall-through fetches. Hot CoreMark loop targets should hit after warmup and\\nsave one redirect bubble with much lower timing risk than the failed IF-side\\nbranch, BTB, RAS, loop, JAL, and stall-shadow predictors.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"...\n  Line 35: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r12s0\", \"title\": \"Pipeline low-half MUL partials\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The best current bench result came from moving low-half MUL out of the\\ncommon ALU cone, but the standalone mul_unit still contains a full 32x32\\nproduct path that must meet the FPGA clock. Prior attempts show that\\nreintroducing multiplier logic into EX, folding MUL into the shared M unit,\\nor adding operand-class bypasses regresses QoR. A narrower MUL-only internal\\ndatapath keeps the successful isolation while attacking the remaining\\nmultiplier timing path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The best current bench result came from moving low-half MUL out of the\\ncommon ALU cone, but the standalone mul_unit still contains a full 32x32\\nproduct path that must meet the FPGA clock. Prior attempts show that\\nreintroducing multiplier logic into EX, folding MUL into the shared M unit,\\nor adding operand-class bypasses regresses QoR. A narrower MUL-only internal\\ndatapath keeps the successful isolation while attacking the remaining\\nmultiplier timing path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Rewrite rtl/mul_unit.sv so the real hardware path computes RV32 MUL[31:0]\\nover a few registered partial-product phases, for example by capturing\\n16x16 low and cross partials, then summing only the low 32 result bits in a\\nlater cycle. Keep the same start/result_valid/result_ready interface, keep\\nthe RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS branch simple and equivalent, and let EX continue to\\nhold only while mul_unit is busy. This adds one or two cycles only to sparse\\nlow-half MUL instructions, while potentially replacing the current 32x32\\nregister-to-register product path with shorter 16x16 multiply and 32-bit add\\nstages for better Tang Nano Fmax.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mul_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the single-cycle 32x32 real-product datapath with a small multicycle low-half partial-product pipeline while preserving ...\n  Line 36: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r12s1\", \"title\": \"Predecode M dispatch flags\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The best structural gains for this core came from keeping RV32M arithmetic\\noff the common EX path and from registering forwarding decisions before EX.\\nThe current EX stage still re-decodes the registered ALU op every cycle to\\nclassify low-half MUL versus slow MULH/DIV/REM work, and those compare\\nresults feed the EX stall, start, ready, and result-select cones. A small\\nID-stage retime can shorten that control path without changing CoreMark IPC\\nor adding predictor, memory, or bypass machinery that has regressed before.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The best structural gains for this core came from keeping RV32M arithmetic\\noff the common EX path and from registering forwarding decisions before EX.\\nThe current EX stage still re-decodes the registered ALU op every cycle to\\nclassify low-half MUL versus slow MULH/DIV/REM work, and those compare\\nresults feed the EX stall, start, ready, and result-select cones. A small\\nID-stage retime can shorten that control path without changing CoreMark IPC\\nor adding predictor, memory, or bypass machinery that has regressed before.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add registered M-dispatch metadata to the ID/EX payload: one flag for\\nALU_MUL and one flag for the slow high-half/DIV/REM RV32M group, computed\\nonce in decode from the already-decoded alu_op and valid legality context.\\nEX should use these registered flags for mul_start, m_start, ex_slow_busy,\\nresult_ready, operand latching, and the M-result select, while preserving\\nthe separate one-cycle mul_unit and the existing multi-cycle m_unit. This\\nfollows the proven pattern of moving small compare/priority decisions out\\nof the EX cone, avoids reconnecting MUL to the slow shared unit, and should\\nprovide a modest Fmax-driven fitness gain with no intentional cycle-count\\nchange.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\":...\n  Line 37: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r12s2\", \"title\": \"Decode return target predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Prior predictor experiments on this core repeatedly lost Fmax by putting\\nbranch target adders, tag compares, BTB/RAS reads, or replay muxing on the\\nfetch next-PC path. The least costly remaining control-flow opportunity is\\ncanonical function returns: CoreMark still has call/return structure, and a\\nreturn target is already available as the decoded rs1 register value for\\nwell-spaced `jalr x0, 0(x1/x5)` instructions.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior predictor experiments on this core repeatedly lost Fmax by putting\\nbranch target adders, tag compares, BTB/RAS reads, or replay muxing on the\\nfetch next-PC path. The least costly remaining control-flow opportunity is\\ncanonical function returns: CoreMark still has call/return structure, and a\\nreturn target is already available as the decoded rs1 register value for\\nwell-spaced `jalr x0, 0(x1/x5)` instructions.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a decode-stage exact return target predictor for canonical returns only.\\nWhen ID sees `jalr x0, 0(x1)` or `jalr x0, 0(x5)`, the instruction is valid,\\nID is not stalled/flushed, the rs1 value does not need EX/MEM forwarding, and\\nthe cleared JALR target is word-aligned, redirect IF to that register target\\none cycle before the existing EX JALR redirect. Carry a compact predicted-ret\\nbit and target in ID/EX so EX suppresses the normal redirect only when the\\nresolved target matches; all forwarded, misaligned, or mismatching cases fall\\nback to the current EX redirect/trap behavior. This targets return bubbles\\nwith much less timing risk than the failed IF-side RAS, BTB, JAL, loop, and\\nreplay predictors because there is no fetch-stage instruction decode, target\\naddition, stack lookup, or tag compare on the common fall-through path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 1, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add compa...","metadata":{"matches":32,"truncated":false},"title":"predict|BTB|RAS|branch|return|JAL|loop|replay","time":{"start":1778616489863,"end":1778616489893}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_009dfc4ff09270de016a0388a9b9e481989bd4f1f12707a193"}},"id":"prt_e1dcdd781001ZONCL0xQRdqfQn","sessionID":"ses_1e2326672ffeu6SPYP8feizLrS","messageID":"msg_e1dcd9a00001MBg2pCLMIEYYmM"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778616489908,"sessionID":"ses_1e2326672ffeu6SPYP8feizLrS","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"glob","callID":"call_dmpwLU0mQKHLgkj3IwX25Y0a","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r13s2.yaml","path":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1"},"output":"No files found","metadata":{"count":0,"truncated":false},"title":"","time":{"start":1778616489871,"end":1778616489907}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_009dfc4ff09270de016a0388a9b9ec8198bc751f0f18b3fcce"}},"id":"prt_e1dcdd78a001gqm5c7zBEQapEK","sessionID":"ses_1e2326672ffeu6SPYP8feizLrS","messageID":"msg_e1dcd9a00001MBg2pCLMIEYYmM"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778616489911,"sessionID":"ses_1e2326672ffeu6SPYP8feizLrS","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_e1oc4W0wFqF0lIGuQSpMP4KY","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/LESSONS.md","offset":1,"limit":260},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/LESSONS.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r1s0 (regression, +23.72%): Single-cycle RV32M datapath sharing can worsen FPGA timing because sign-select muxing, 33x33 multiply width, and quotient-derived remainder logic stay in the EX output cone despite reducing source-level arithmetic duplication.\n2: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r1s1 (improvement, +30.41%): Keeping only low-half MUL on the single-cycle EX path while moving rare high-half multiply and DIV/REM ops into a stalling m_unit removes slow RV32M mux cones from CoreMark's hot path and materially improves Fmax.\n3: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r1s2 (regression, +13.57%): Static backward/JAL prediction can lose more to the IF-stage next-PC critical cone (immediate decode, PC+target add, alignment muxing) than it saves in CoreMark EX redirect flushes.\n4: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r2s0 (regression, -1.23%): Manual 16-bit partial-product decomposition for MUL[31:0] can regress FPGA fitness because it forces three multiplies and cross-product adders into the EX cone instead of letting synthesis trim a single inferred `a * b`.\n5: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r2s1 (regression, -16.67%): Elastic IF buffering can lose on this CoreMark target when buffer valid/data/PC muxing and queue control add more frontend timing cost than random imem-stall overlap can repay.\n6: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r2s2 (regression, -5.44%): EX-trained tiny BTB prediction still regressed CoreMark; even without IF target recompute, the valid/tag/counter/target array read plus compare and next-PC mux added more fetch-side cost than saved redirect bubbles.\n7: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r3s0 (improvement, +3.22%): Splitting slow RV32M finalization into an unsigned last iteration plus a finish cycle can improve Fmax because sign correction and result selection leave the iterative m_unit carry/mux cone while CoreMark rarely pays the added latency.\n8: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r3s1 (regression, -30.29%): MEM-to-EX load-use bypass regressed because dmem-ready/load-extension validity and extra forwarding wait muxes added more backend timing/control cost than saved CoreMark's single-cycle load-use bubbles.\n9: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r3s2 (regression, -35.63%): Even a single-entry EX-trained backward-loop predictor regressed CoreMark, implying the IF exact-PC hit compare/next-PC mux plus ID/EX `pred_pc` redirect-suppression compare costs more timing/control than the saved taken-loop flushes.\n10: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r4s0 (regression, -1.03%): Replacing MEM byte-lane shifts with explicit case muxes can slightly regress FPGA fitness because synthesis already handles small lane shifts well and manual lane decode/muxing stays on every load/store path.\n11: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r4s1 (improvement, +1.58%): Registering decode-time forwarding selects gives a small fitness gain by moving rd/rs compare and priority logic out of the EX ALU/MUL operand cone, as long as load-use bubbles and non-forwardable load/jump cases are preserved.\n12: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r4s2 (regression, -3.19%): Even canonical-ret-only RAS prediction can regress CoreMark because the IF `imem_data` return compare, RAS top/index read, and next-PC mux cost more timing than saved JALR redirect bubbles.\n13: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r5s0 (regression, -5.72%): Source-use-qualified load-use detection regressed because CoreMark's false load-use bubbles are cheaper than adding IF/ID opcode source decode and qualified hazard control to the stall path.\n14: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r5s1 (regression, -1.42%): Registering MEM/WB writeback data regressed slightly because the WB result mux was not the binding EX forwarding path, while the extra 32-bit MEM/WB field/register increased backend state/fanout without changing CoreMark IPC.\n15: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r5s2 (regression, -47.75%): Decode-stage direct-JAL prediction can be worse than EX redirect because it creates an ID decode/imm-add to IF next-PC feedback path plus EX redirect-suppression and forwarding exceptions for bubbles CoreMark does not repay.\n16: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r6s0 (regression, -2.27%): Precomputing `pc+4` and `pc+imm` into ID/EX can regress when the extra 64 bits of pipeline state and ID-side adders cost more routing/timing than removing EX PC adders and the AUIPC ALU-input mux saves.\n17: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r6s1 (regression, -10.63%): Pruning seemingly dead EX/MEM `branch_taken`/`branch_target` and `ctrl.is_lui` sidebands can hurt QoR because those fields were not the timing bottleneck and RTL reshaping perturbed synthesis without improving IPC.\n18: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r6s2 (regression, -23.60%): Removing loop predictor tag/PC compares was still not enough for CoreMark; countdown predictor state, IF next-PC muxing, and ID/EX prediction-recovery metadata kept the control path cost above the saved loop-redirect bubbles.\n19: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r7s0 (regression, -10.54%): Manually sharing EX branch compare flags can hurt QoR because synthesis already optimizes equality/range inversions, while the explicit `cmp_ltu`/sign-correction flag network adds fanout and muxing on the branch redirect path.\n20: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r7s1 (regression, -3.68%): Duplicating the regfile into unreset LUTRAM read banks can cost more write fanout and LUT/read-mux routing than it saves in resettable flops, so the reset-cleared flop regfile was not the binding CoreMark timing/area path.\n21: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r7s2 (regression, -31.57%): Registering a one-fetch-ahead loop predictor still regressed CoreMark because the IF next-PC mux, `pred_taken`/`pred_target` sidebands, and EX prediction-mismatch recovery compare outweighed saved backward-branch redirects.\n22: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r8s0 (regression, -28.60%): Narrowing the slow MULH loop's source-level adder was not enough; the right-shift product register added wide feedback/shift routing, so the original 64-bit iterative carry chain was not the binding CoreMark timing path.\n23: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r8s1 (improvement, +2.88%): Registering low-half `ALU_MUL` behind an EX hold removes the 32x32 multiplier from the common ADD/load-address/branch ALU cone, and CoreMark's sparse MUL use repays the extra bubble with modest Fmax-driven fitness gain.\n24: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r8s2 (regression, -47.78%): Even a JAL-only target cache that avoids IF immediate adds can regress badly because valid/tag/target lookup, next-PC muxing, prediction sidebands, and jump-forwarding exceptions outweigh CoreMark's direct-JAL flush savings.\n25: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r9s0 (regression, -2.51%): Splitting EX/MEM result selection into separate M-ready commit branches did not help because synthesis had already kept rare M results off the hot fast path, while extra priority/control muxing around `m_waiting` and ready selects slightly hurt QoR.\n26: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r9s1 (regression, -9.88%): Folding registered low-half `ALU_MUL` into the shared `m_unit` can lose the r8 timing win because common start/valid/result muxing reconnects MUL to high-half/DIV/REM side-unit control instead of preserving a narrow isolated product path.\n27: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r9s2 (regression, -10.88%): Stall-shadow prediction still costs real QoR because IF-held predecode/target adders, shadow PC/instr matching, EX mismatch recovery, and jump-forwarding exceptions outweighed CoreMark bubbles saved during random stalls.\n28: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r10s0 (regression, -3.69%): Control-only pipeline resets can regress QoR when per-field side-effect masks and added `in.valid` gating increase EX redirect/register control muxing more than reduced datapath reset fanout saves.\n29: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r10s1 (regression, -8.58%): A one-entry posted store buffer can lose on CoreMark when pending-store ordering hazards and dmem port muxing add more MEM/stall-path timing/control cost than independent work behind stalled stores can hide.\n30: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r10s2 (regression, -16.25%): Exact trivial-MUL bypass can undo the registered-MUL timing win when zero/one/minus-one operand compares and fast-result muxing re-enter the EX commit/stall cone, since CoreMark has too few repayable trivial MUL bubbles.\n31: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r11s0 (regression, -32.95%): Source-level sharing of EX `pc_plus4`/`pc_imm_sum` can hurt QoR because forced fanout and AUIPC result-boundary muxing couple PC adders into redirect/result cones that synthesis was better able to duplicate or trim locally.\n32: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r11s1 (regression, -15.66%): Splitting MEM/WB stall retention into a narrow WB forwarding shadow can regress because the shadow-valid mux lands directly on the EX MEM/WB-forwarding operand path while the old wide `hold_mem_wb` bundle fanout was not the binding path.\n33: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r11s2 (regression, -70.72%): Redirect-only target replay still regressed badly because the redirect-target tag compare, cached-instruction/pc+4 injection muxes, and `redirect_inject` hazard/forwarding exceptions moved predictor cost onto the EX redirect path instead of the fall-through fetch path.\n34: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r12s0 (regression, -13.66%): Pipelining isolated low-half MUL into 16x16 partial phases can still lose because three partial multipliers, sum state, and added MUL stall cycles outweigh any Fmax benefit over a single inferred registered `a * b`.\n35: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r12s1 (regression, -3.50%): Predecoding M-dispatch flags can slightly regress QoR because extra ID/EX sideband flops and decode valid/legal gating cost more than removing small `alu_op` compares from the EX M-control cone.\n36: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r12s2 (regression, -13.26%): Decode-stage canonical-return prediction still regressed because ID regfile/forwarding/alignment checks feed an IF next-PC redirect path and add ID/EX `pred_ret` suppression state, so avoiding IF-side RAS/tag lookup was not enough to make return prediction cheap for CoreMark.\n\n(End of file - total 36 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r1s0 (regression, +23.72%): Single-cycle RV32M datapath sharing can worsen FPGA timing because sign-select muxing, 33x33 multiply width, and quotient-derived remainder logic stay in the EX output cone despite reducing source-level arithmetic duplication.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r1s1 (improvement, +30.41%): Keeping only low-half MUL on the single-cycle EX path while moving rare high-half multiply and DIV/REM ops into a stalling m_unit removes slow RV32M mux cones from CoreMark's hot path and materially improves Fmax.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r1s2 (regression, +13.57%): Static backward/JAL prediction can lose more to the IF-stage next-PC critical cone (immediate decode, PC+target add, alignment muxing) than it saves in CoreMark EX redirect flushes.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r2s0 (regression, -1.23%): Manual 16-bit partial-product decomposition for MUL[31:0] can regress FPGA fitness because it forces three multiplies and cross-product adders into the EX cone instead of letting synthesis trim a single inferred `a * b`.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r2s1 (regression, -16.67%): Elastic IF buffering can lose on this CoreMark target when buffer valid/data/PC muxing and queue control add more frontend timing cost than random imem-stall overlap can repay.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r2s2 (regression, -5.44%): EX-trained tiny BTB prediction still regressed CoreMark; even without IF target recompute, the valid/tag/counter/target array read plus compare and next-PC mux added more fetch-side cost than saved redirect bubbles.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r3s0 (improvement, +3.22%): Splitting slow RV32M finalization into an unsigned last iteration plus a finish cycle can improve Fmax because sign correction and result selection leave the iterative m_unit carry/mux cone while CoreMark rarely pays the added latency.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r3s1 (regression, -30.29%): MEM-to-EX load-use bypass regressed because dmem-ready/load-extension validity and extra forwarding wait muxes added more backend timing/control cost than saved CoreMark's single-cycle load-use bubbles.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r3s2 (regression, -35.63%): Even a single-entry EX-trained backward-loop predictor regressed CoreMark, implying the IF exact-PC hit compare/next-PC mux plus ID/EX `pred_pc` redirect-suppression compare costs more timing/control than the saved taken-loop flushes.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r4s0 (regression, -1.03%): Replacing MEM byte-lane shifts with explicit case muxes can slightly regress FPGA fitness because synthesis already handles small lane shifts well and manual lane decode/muxing stays on every load/store path.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r4s1 (improvement, +1.58%): Registering decode-time forwarding selects gives a small fitness gain by moving rd/rs compare and priority logic out of the EX ALU/MUL operand cone, as long as load-use bubbles and non-forwardable load/jump cases are preserved.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r4s2 (regression, -3.19%): Even canonical-ret-only RAS prediction can regress CoreMark because the IF `imem_data` return compare, RAS top/index read, and next-PC mux cost more timing than saved JALR redirect bubbles.\n- 20