{"type":"text","timestamp":1778616527415,"sessionID":"ses_1e2326672ffeu6SPYP8feizLrS","part":{"id":"prt_e1dce6880001ZdZuhFpw1A0c4b","messageID":"msg_e1dcdd807001mI2UV1ug1Wqd8Z","sessionID":"ses_1e2326672ffeu6SPYP8feizLrS","type":"text","text":"The prior predictor log is consistently negative when the predictor touches the normal IF next-PC cone, adds prediction sidebands, or adds EX redirect-suppression compares. I’m going to write a narrower predictor hypothesis that targets a different control hazard: using predicted branch bubbles as an opportunity to run ahead sequentially only after a predicted-not-taken branch proves taken, without changing the common fall-through PC path.","time":{"start":1778616526976,"end":1778616527413},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0a3d2d1be3714fdb016a0388cedaf08198bd996d2be5e410bf","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1778616602453,"sessionID":"ses_1e2326672ffeu6SPYP8feizLrS","part":{"id":"prt_e1dcf8ef8001E1ABLDSPuffoIy","messageID":"msg_e1dcdd807001mI2UV1ug1Wqd8Z","sessionID":"ses_1e2326672ffeu6SPYP8feizLrS","type":"text","text":"I’ll create the hypothesis file now. The proposal avoids IF lookup/target prediction and instead uses static branch direction only at EX, with MEM-stage verification, betting on Fmax improvement without adding fetch-path predictor machinery.","time":{"start":1778616602360,"end":1778616602452},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0a3d2d1be3714fdb016a03891a37208198bf10f8233d9a2aee","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778616612623,"sessionID":"ses_1e2326672ffeu6SPYP8feizLrS","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_Q9uihDc0oL3MISgjajYR5QlE","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r13s2.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-003-r13s2\n+title: \"Speculative EX branch direction\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  Every prior frontend predictor for this core has lost more FPGA timing than\n+  it recovered in CoreMark cycles because lookup, target generation, or\n+  prediction metadata landed on the IF next-PC path. The remaining predictor\n+  opportunity is to keep fetch as simple fall-through-plus-redirect while\n+  shortening the EX redirect decision itself.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Predict conditional branch direction in EX with the cheap static heuristic\n+  already implied by CoreMark loop structure: backward branches predict taken,\n+  forward branches predict not taken. Use that prediction to drive the EX\n+  redirect path without waiting for the full rs1/rs2 branch comparator, then\n+  verify the actual branch condition one stage later in MEM and issue an older\n+  late redirect on mismatch. Correct backward-loop iterations keep the current\n+  redirect timing, loop exits pay a one-cycle-later recovery, and the normal IF\n+  fall-through path gains no BTB, RAS, target-cache, or instruction-predecode\n+  logic. If the branch comparator/control fanout is part of the current Tang\n+  Nano critical path, this should trade a small number of extra loop-exit\n+  bubbles for a modest Fmax gain.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add EX/MEM branch prediction metadata and enough branch operand/control fields for MEM-stage verification and correct RVFI pc_wdata.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Drive conditional-branch redirects from a static backward-taken EX prediction while carrying actual-compare inputs forward instead of resolving redirect from the comparator.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Verify predicted branch direction, compute the architectural branch pc_next for MEM/WB/RVFI, and expose late-redirect target/mismatch signals.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Merge older MEM-stage late redirects with normal EX redirects, giving late branch recovery priority and preserving the nret=1 RVFI port contract.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Flush younger IF/ID, ID/EX, and EX/MEM work on a MEM-stage branch-prediction mismatch while keeping existing load-use, dmem, imem, and slow-M stalls intact.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r13s2.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r13s2.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r13s2.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r13s2.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,35 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-003-r13s2\n+title: \"Speculative EX branch direction\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  Every prior frontend predictor for this core has lost more FPGA timing than\n+  it recovered in CoreMark cycles because lookup, target generation, or\n+  prediction metadata landed on the IF next-PC path. The remaining predictor\n+  opportunity is to keep fetch as simple fall-through-plus-redirect while\n+  shortening the EX redirect decision itself.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Predict conditional branch direction in EX with the cheap static heuristic\n+  already implied by Core