{"type":"text","timestamp":1778600117609,"sessionID":"ses_1e32f1853ffe0LLa9SLFCt6452","part":{"id":"prt_e1cd3fd8b001z0Vox2OV01ein6","messageID":"msg_e1cd13984001b7sd1frfc7Rxkh","sessionID":"ses_1e32f1853ffe0LLa9SLFCt6452","type":"text","text":"The prior predictor failures all added fetch-side target calculation or PC/tag compare logic. I’m writing a narrower return-address-stack predictor hypothesis that only predicts canonical `ret` JALR instructions from a registered stack top, avoiding branch target adders and BTB tag arrays in IF.","time":{"start":1778600115595,"end":1778600117608},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0be97698fd4e2f1d016a0348b3674481948b666f8fd5d3e0eb","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778600138341,"sessionID":"ses_1e32f1853ffe0LLa9SLFCt6452","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_E3MDdM8KA4EE3zOtw7ramHZF","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r4s2.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-003-r4s2\n+title: \"Tiny RAS return predictor\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  Prior branch predictors regressed because they put target adders, tag compares,\n+  or predicted-PC metadata on already-sensitive frontend and EX paths. CoreMark\n+  still executes call/return control flow around its benchmark kernels, and\n+  returns are predictable with much less IF logic than conditional branches or a\n+  BTB: an exact `ret` instruction compare plus a registered return-stack top.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a tiny return-address-stack predictor for canonical RISC-V returns only.\n+  Train the stack when EX resolves link-register JAL/JALR calls, and when IF\n+  fetches `jalr x0, 0(x1)` or `jalr x0, 0(x5)` with a valid stack entry, use the\n+  stored top as the next PC. Carry only return-prediction metadata to EX so a\n+  correctly predicted return suppresses the normal JALR redirect, while a bad or\n+  empty-stack prediction redirects to the architecturally resolved target. This\n+  should recover return redirect bubbles with far less timing cost than the\n+  failed static branch, BTB, and loop-target predictors because IF does not\n+  compute branch immediates, add targets, or compare fetch PCs against tags.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add compact return-prediction metadata to IF/ID and ID/EX bundles for EX redirect suppression and recovery.\"\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a tiny registered return-address stack, exact canonical-ret detection, and EX-trained push/pop inputs without adding branch target arithmetic to IF.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Detect link-register calls and canonical returns, provide RAS update signals, and suppress JALR redirects only when the carried return prediction matches the resolved target.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire RAS prediction/update signals between IF and EX while preserving the nret=1 RVFI port contract.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r4s2.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r4s2.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r4s2.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r4s2.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,31 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-003-r4s2\n+title: \"Tiny RAS return predictor\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  Prior branch predictors regressed because they put target adders, tag compares,\n+  or predicted-PC metadata on already-sensitive frontend and EX paths. CoreMark\n+  still executes call/return control flow around its benchmark kernels, and\n+  returns are predictable with much less IF logic than conditional branches or a\n+  BTB: an exact `ret` instruction compare plus a registered return-stack top.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a tiny return-address-stack predictor for canonical RISC-V returns only.\n+  Train the stack when EX resolves link-register JAL/JALR calls, and when IF\n+  fetches `jalr x0, 0(x1)` or `jalr x0, 0(x5)` with a valid stack entry, use the\n+  stored top as the next PC. Carry only return-prediction metadata to EX so a\n+  correctly predicted return suppresses the normal JALR redirect, while a bad 