{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778603246760,"sessionID":"ses_1e2fed6b7ffe97xjpoVKWRiGv7","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_Femey1yMpW3Cl4uPkLtIXQ8k","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r6s2.yaml","offset":1,"limit":120},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r6s2.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260512-003-r6s2\n2: title: \"Countdown loop predictor\"\n3: category: predictor\n4: motivation: |\n5:   Prior predictor attempts recovered possible control-flow cycles but lost more\n6:   FPGA fitness through fetch-side instruction decode, target adders, BTB/RAS\n7:   lookup, or exact PC compare paths. CoreMark is still loop-heavy, so the most\n8:   promising remaining predictor angle is to keep loop prediction state cheap\n9:   enough that it does not dominate the IF next-PC cone.\n10: hypothesis: |\n11:   Add a single-entry backward-loop countdown predictor trained by EX when a\n12:   conditional branch resolves taken to a lower PC. Store the loop target and\n13:   the branch-to-target distance in words, then count sequential fetch advances\n14:   from the target; when the counter reaches zero, predict the stored loop\n15:   target without decoding the fetched instruction or comparing the fetch PC\n16:   against a tag. Carry compact prediction metadata through ID/EX so EX can\n17:   suppress the normal taken-branch redirect on a correct loop prediction and\n18:   recover to pc+4 on the loop exit or any mismatch. This should preserve most\n19:   of the useful inner-loop benefit of the failed loop/BTB predictors while\n20:   replacing the IF exact-PC/tag compare with a small zero-count check.\n21: expected_impact:\n22:   fitness_delta_pct: 2\n23:   confidence: low\n24: changes:\n25:   - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n26:     description: \"Add compact predicted-loop-taken and predicted-target metadata to IF/ID and ID/EX bundles.\"\n27:   - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n28:     description: \"Add the single-entry backward-loop countdown predictor, update it on resolved branch training, and select the stored target only when the countdown reaches zero.\"\n29:   - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n30:     description: \"Propagate the IF-stage loop prediction metadata through the ID/EX register without changing decode legality behavior.\"\n31:   - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n32:     description: \"Expose backward-branch training information and use the carried prediction metadata to suppress correct predicted-loop redirects or recover on loop exit/mismatch.\"\n33:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n34:     description: \"Wire EX loop-training signals back to IF while preserving the nret=1 RVFI port contract.\"\n\n(End of file - total 34 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260512-003-r6s2\ntitle: \"Countdown loop predictor\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  Prior predictor attempts recovered possible control-flow cycles but lost more\n  FPGA fitness through fetch-side instruction decode, target adders, BTB/RAS\n  lookup, or exact PC compare paths. CoreMark is still loop-heavy, so the most\n  promising remaining predictor angle is to keep loop prediction state cheap\n  enough that it does not dominate the IF next-PC cone.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a single-entry backward-loop countdown predictor trained by EX when a\n  conditional branch resolves taken to a lower PC. Store the loop target and\n  the branch-to-target distance in words, then count sequential fetch advances\n  from the target; when the counter reaches zero, predict the stored loop\n  target without decoding the fetched instruction or comparing the fetch PC\n  against a tag. Carry compact prediction metadata through ID/EX so EX can\n  suppress the normal taken-branch redirect on a correct loop prediction and\n  recover to pc+4 on the loop exit or any mismatch. This should preserve most\n  of the useful inner-loop benefit of the failed loop/BTB predictors while\n  replacing the IF exact-PC/tag compare with a small zero-count check.","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r6s2.yaml","time":{"start":1778603246753,"end":1778603246759}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_06102a6c9bd43f30016a0354ed6fc8819bbdb705136b7e687d"}},"id":"prt_e1d03bfec001Wgx0TCiHS5Mqu1","sessionID":"ses_1e2fed6b7ffe97xjpoVKWRiGv7","messageID":"msg_e1d03a6b2001aDdAVQ7g5ODQI2"}}
